{"term":"1965","caseName":"United States v. Johnson","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1965/25","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - November 10, 1965","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren13/oral_argument_audio/14881","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"No.25, United States, petitioner versus Thomas Johnson.","start":0,"stop":50.123,"duration":50.12}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":50.123,"stop":51.504,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Miss Rosenberg.","start":51.504,"stop":54.244,"duration":2.74}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":54.244,"stop":57.429,"duration":3.19},{"text":"This case in here on writ of certiorari to the United States Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit to reveal its judgment, reversing on the conviction respondent for conspiracy to defraud the United States.","start":57.429,"stop":72.88,"duration":15.45},{"text":"The charges against respondent which the jury and for that matter the Court of Appeals found established by the evidence, were that he used, that he took money to use his position as a Congressman in the interest to co-defendants represented so called independent Maryland Savings and Loan Association, first to make a speech on the floor of Congress and then to use his Congressional influence to bear on the Department of Justice to get it, to dismiss an indictment against his co-defendant and one of its companies, first calling.","start":72.88,"stop":119.797,"duration":46.92},{"text":"The Court of Appeals reversed the conviction solely because it reached the conclusion that it was beyond the power of Congress to provide where the prosecution of a Congressman for taking money to make its speech on the floor of Congress.","start":119.797,"stop":141.123,"duration":21.33},{"text":"It reversed the conviction on substantive counts, which did not involve the speech at all but only the representations to the Department of Justice, only because it felt that the evidence we laid into the speech part of the conspiracy might have influenced the verdict of the jury on the other counts.","start":141.123,"stop":163.929,"duration":22.81},{"text":"And so the question that we brought to the Court and the only question that we think it's properly involved in this case now revolves around the taking of money to give a speech on the floor of Congress.","start":163.929,"stop":180.814,"duration":16.88}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well was there a new trial on the other phase of it?","start":180.814,"stop":184.018,"duration":3.2}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"It ordered a new trial on the other phase and we have not brought that issue here.","start":184.018,"stop":190.053,"duration":6.03},{"text":"We referred in our petition but we did not argue it, I might say largely because it cannot be determined without reaching -- reading the whole record.","start":190.053,"stop":202.705,"duration":12.65},{"text":"The question in this case which we did bring here and which we think it's a question involved is this.","start":202.705,"stop":209.417,"duration":6.71},{"text":"Article 1, Section 6 of the Constitution provides that for any speech or debate in either House, no member of Congress shall be questioned in any other place.","start":209.417,"stop":227.667,"duration":18.25},{"text":"And as we view it, the question is, does that Speech or Debate Clause means that Congress is without power under the Constitution to make it a crime triable in a court for a Congressman to take money to make a speech.","start":227.667,"stop":252.051,"duration":24.38},{"text":"And the opinion of Court of Appeals --","start":252.051,"stop":253.96,"duration":1.91}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask under what statute Congress has made it a crime?","start":253.96,"stop":258.209,"duration":4.25}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"What Congress had, specifically made it a crime at what was formally 18 U.S.C. 205.","start":258.209,"stop":264.581,"duration":6.37},{"text":"I think my opponent will dispute this, because he says if a speech wasn't have to a matter then pending it wasn't.","start":264.581,"stop":271.641,"duration":7.06},{"text":"This indictment was brought under as a conspiracy to defraud the United States of the good offices of a Congressman in two parts; one to make the speech and the other to bring his influence to bear on the Department of Justice and so what was charged is the conspiracy under 371, but the way the Court of Appeals decided the question, it is no doubt I think if you will look at its opinion which is in volume 3 that it was deciding it very broadly, said it was beyond the power of Congress to make it a crime to take money for anything that came within the Speech and Debate Clause, which under this Court Kilbourn decision means more than speech.","start":271.641,"stop":325.341,"duration":53.7},{"text":"It means speech or vote or committee report or anything in a sense which is official action and so that's the way that Court of Appeals decided the case that the Speech or Debate Clause by its terms made it constitutionally impossible for Congress to make the taking of money or bribery a crime for anything done within the protection of that clause.","start":325.341,"stop":356.471,"duration":31.13},{"text":"And this would cover 205 as well as the aspect of 371 with which we are here concerned and now I think it is helpful both for the general problem on which case was decided and for this particular case, if we consider first that general preposition which the Court of Appeals decided and then turn to that particular fact that this case to see whether there's special problems arising out of the fact that it was charged under 371 or in the particular prosecution here.","start":356.471,"stop":394.8,"duration":38.33},{"text":"The government's basic position is that a prosecution for taking money to make a speech does not question that speech within the meaning of the Speech or Debate Clause because what is being questioned is not the speech, but the taking of the money and the taking of the money of course is not official action and does not occur on the floor commonly.","start":394.8,"stop":424.858,"duration":30.06},{"text":"I don't think analytically there can be any problem with that.","start":424.858,"stop":428.273,"duration":3.42},{"text":"It's obvious that the taking of money is not something that's official action on the floor of Congress and I think that it becomes clear if one hypothesizes a situation where a Congressman, where the evidence is discovered immediately, let's say by a tape recorder and a Congressman is arrested immediately before he had given the speech for which he took money.","start":428.273,"stop":458.986,"duration":30.71},{"text":"In that case he would come within a bribery statute.","start":458.986,"stop":463.009,"duration":4.02},{"text":"He would be prosecuted for taking money to make a speech, but the speech would never had been given then the Speech and Debate Clause would never come into play.","start":463.009,"stop":472.036,"duration":9.03},{"text":"Now of course we realize that the question isn't normally that simple.","start":472.036,"stop":477.209,"duration":5.17},{"text":"Normally --","start":477.209,"stop":478.28,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":478.28,"stop":485.751,"duration":7.47}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I am coming -- the content of the speech was not relied on by the government.","start":485.751,"stop":491.99,"duration":6.24},{"text":"The only copy of the speech which the government introduced was a reprint, ordered by his co-conspirator.","start":491.99,"stop":499.041,"duration":7.05}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Why was it introduced?","start":499.041,"stop":500.934,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it would introduce to show it was one apart of the evidence, showing that money was taken for the speech, but let me point out that the reprint that was introduced was in at least one significant respect different from the speech that was given, because the caption was changed on the reprint.","start":500.934,"stop":521.138,"duration":20.2},{"text":"The caption on the original speech which the government did not introduce, dependent introduced the original speech, caption on the original speech was something like the Maryland Savings and Loan industry.","start":521.138,"stop":534.047,"duration":12.91},{"text":"The caption on the reprint that was introduced was Federal Savings and Loan leaves seek discretion of competitive independence and commercial mortgage insurance.","start":534.047,"stop":554.334,"duration":20.29},{"text":"Now of course the government gave evidence about the speech, it gave reasons about how it was prepared and what use was made of it by the co-conspirators.","start":554.334,"stop":564.406,"duration":10.07},{"text":"Of course it was the government's theory that money was given to make a speech, but it was not, the content of the speech was not part of the governments plan.","start":564.406,"stop":574.92,"duration":10.51},{"text":"And they also say it came in a --","start":574.92,"stop":576.337,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well was anything that was said in the speech relied on by the government to support the conviction?","start":576.337,"stop":581.577,"duration":5.24}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"After doing -- not as part of government affirmative case.","start":581.577,"stop":586.147,"duration":4.57}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well at any time in the trial?","start":586.147,"stop":587.278,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, after the defendant took the stand, he was cross examined about some statements in the speech and they were commented upon in oral argument, but if the government in its affirmative case did not rely on the content of the speech or the government relied on was on other evidence, but as I say leaning that out as the moment the specific problems here, the question was Court of Appeals deciding is not that.","start":587.278,"stop":617.96,"duration":30.68},{"text":"It did not decide simply that it was too much reference to the speech in this case.","start":617.96,"stop":622.829,"duration":4.87},{"text":"It's said much more broadly that it is beyond the competence of Congress to provide for to make it a crime, to take money to make a speech and the reasoning of the Court of Appeals as I understand it is this.","start":622.829,"stop":643.849,"duration":21.02},{"text":"No matter how strong the evidence, even if the government never even introduces the speech, assuming the speech has once been given, as it would be in the normal case, no matter how strong the evidence the government introduces, any Congressman who can't deny that he took money.","start":643.849,"stop":666.095,"duration":22.25},{"text":"Its of course would be the best, but assuming he can't deny that he took money, he will be called upon to explain, he will feel compelled to explain that he gave the money – that he gave a speech not for money but for some other reason.","start":666.095,"stop":684.718,"duration":18.62},{"text":"And therefore taking the language out of cases like this Court's decision in Tenney against Brandhove, which says that the motives of official action cannot be questioned.","start":684.718,"stop":701.388,"duration":16.67},{"text":"The Court of Appeals said you bring motive into the case, because the Congressman will feel compelled to explain his motives and that's not the speech in debate clause, but as we see it, there is a big difference between this situation and Tenney and others like it [Inaudible] is that when you bring an action in libel which what Tenney was or where the Speech and Debate Clause got started, where the king brought an action for sedition or treason or criminal libel so that either civilly or criminally whenever this is done, the affirmative part of the plaintiffs case is that you prove the speech, the content of the speech.","start":701.388,"stop":761.849,"duration":60.46},{"text":"You prove that the contents were injurious, that it results in the injury, either to the individual bringing the action or to the state because the contents were treasonable or seditious in the old days and that this injury was caused by a bad motive and the Court said no.","start":761.849,"stop":788.729,"duration":26.88},{"text":"That's too dangerous to free speech.","start":788.729,"stop":792.622,"duration":3.89},{"text":"They said and the reason of it I think it's barely evident.","start":792.622,"stop":796.855,"duration":4.23},{"text":"The most noble test at most accurate speech that it can be made can result an injury to someone.","start":796.855,"stop":808.242,"duration":11.39},{"text":"I mean, it's justifiable injury, but it is injury, therefore when you have to start and say this injury is a good motive or bad motive, that becomes court say too difficult.","start":808.242,"stop":825.674,"duration":17.43},{"text":"Because too many actions -- they didn't come a prosecutor brings for example, brings its lawsuit against this defendant to be injured, the defendant will be get in to jail, it's too hard to distinguish if he's doing it for a good motive or a bad.","start":825.674,"stop":840.547,"duration":14.87},{"text":"Its hard to say, is the speech reasonable?","start":840.547,"stop":845.221,"duration":4.67},{"text":"Situation is very different from bribery, because you're not resting on the content of speech to show injury which comes from a bad motive.","start":845.221,"stop":855.518,"duration":10.3},{"text":"What you're resting on is what I said in the beginning, you're resting on the taking of the money and it doesn't matter what the speech is about.","start":855.518,"stop":863.771,"duration":8.25},{"text":"The speech could be the best speech in the world, it could absolutely accurate in every degree, but the injury doesn't come from the speech.","start":863.771,"stop":873.402,"duration":9.63},{"text":"The injury to the government comes from the taking of the money, that's the injury and you don't relay on the contents of the speech even to show injury or you don't rely on the content of a speech as the foundation of your action.","start":873.402,"stop":890.102,"duration":16.7}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"How can you impugn a speech more by saying that it was the product of the bribe?","start":890.102,"stop":897.47,"duration":7.37}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"But you don't rest on the speech, what you rests on is at the act.","start":897.47,"stop":902.143,"duration":4.67},{"text":"The orders of the case of Justice Harlan, you rest on the speech to show the injury and then you say I have been injured by the speech and it was not done for good motives, it was done for a bad motive, but the injury comes from the speech, in bribery the injury doesn't come from the speech.","start":902.143,"stop":924.012,"duration":21.87},{"text":"The injury comes from the taking of the money and it points in this case.","start":924.012,"stop":928.406,"duration":4.39},{"text":"He made it a speech in favor of [Inaudible], which they use but suppose they had a different scheme.","start":928.406,"stop":936.608,"duration":8.2},{"text":"Suppose they have a scheme where one Congressman who's supposed to make a speech for them and a speech against them, each took money because they wanted to make it appear, it wouldn't make any difference, where the one was for them or one was against them, both would be guilty of taking bribes.","start":936.608,"stop":952.599,"duration":15.99},{"text":"The content of the speech don't make any difference.","start":952.599,"stop":955.141,"duration":2.54},{"text":"The injury doesn't come from the content of the speech.","start":955.141,"stop":958.322,"duration":3.18},{"text":"The injury comes from the taking of the money and that's the essential difference between this situation and Tenney and I point out this is not really unique.","start":958.322,"stop":968.672,"duration":10.35},{"text":"We have a principle about judicial decisions, so for as an action for libel or action for treason are concerned the content of the judicial privilege is set.","start":968.672,"stop":981.923,"duration":13.25},{"text":"This Court held back in 231 United States that the principle that a judge couldn't be sued for libel was so much of a part of our system of doing things that it extended to Philippines immediately without any -- as by virtue of the Constitution without any special act of Congress and yet we've always had a statute from 1790 on, we've had a statute making bribery of the judge of crime, there had been prosecution to judges for taking bribe.","start":981.923,"stop":1019.564,"duration":37.64}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The judges aren't surrounded with the constitutional protections?","start":1019.564,"stop":1022.743,"duration":3.18}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well as I point out Mr. Justice, this Court said that the principle that judges cannot be sued or that the content of – decisions cannot be sued for malice was at least so much part of our system of government, I think they consider part of separation of power, that they extend it to the Philippines as a constitutional right, the minute we applied it didn't get the special statute of Congress.","start":1022.743,"stop":1049.434,"duration":26.69},{"text":"So it comes in, in a different historical way.","start":1049.434,"stop":1053.008,"duration":3.57},{"text":"There's no question about that.","start":1053.008,"stop":1055.515,"duration":2.51},{"text":"It came in because judges in the sense were acting the way of not responsible to anybody about themselves and therefore they didn't -- they weren't the problems.","start":1055.515,"stop":1070.006,"duration":14.49},{"text":"The difficulty -- one of the problems of the Speech and Debate Clause I think is that side by side in the beginning with the development of the Speech and Debate Clause was the attempt by parliament to get himself completely out of the crown what was known as the Lex Parliament.","start":1070.006,"stop":1089.583,"duration":19.58},{"text":"And it is sometimes, there's been a tendency to read some of the Lex Parliament into the Speech and Debate Clause and this Court decided in Watkins and had decided before that that that aspect, the power of the parliament just couldn't be reached by the crown at all.","start":1089.583,"stop":1107.076,"duration":17.49},{"text":"It's not a part of an American law.","start":1107.076,"stop":1110.311,"duration":3.23},{"text":"Watkins discusses this at length but and for that reason the the Speech and Debate Clause as I say had the different historical background, but if you look at the contents of it it's not essentially different from the contents of the judicial privilege, which was recognized back in the cases are cited in our brief, but the one that I think is most significant is this Alzua against Johnson in 231 United States where the Court said that a judicial privilege of a judge against sue -- with the claim of Maryland.","start":1110.311,"stop":1148.909,"duration":38.6},{"text":"Extended to the Philippines without just by virtue of the fact that we acquired the Philippines, it is one of those fundamental rights it didn't.","start":1148.909,"stop":1157.928,"duration":9.02}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask you, if the court's charge to the jury indicated that it's finding of guilt should depend in any of those ways on whether the Congressman believed what he said?","start":1157.928,"stop":1171.508,"duration":13.58}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"No, that didn't come in.","start":1171.508,"stop":1174.615,"duration":3.11}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Then as I understood it, if we're to say that the government you say ends up any Congressman takes the money, and action was the speech he made, is guilty of the crime, even though he believed it wholeheartedly?","start":1174.615,"stop":1193.682,"duration":19.07}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"If he takes the money to make the speech.","start":1193.682,"stop":1196.095,"duration":2.41}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if he takes money to make the speech, maybe he's not -- maybe he hadn't intended to make it but he had used to make it, says I believe in it thoroughly and I will make a speech.","start":1196.095,"stop":1206.221,"duration":10.13},{"text":"He gives him the money, would that be a crime?","start":1206.221,"stop":1208.852,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir, Congress so intended I think -- if we did that 201 has now been redrafted, the competence of interest statute had now been redrafted and what was 205, which made it a crime.","start":1208.852,"stop":1225.744,"duration":16.89}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Made it a crime to accept money for a speech?","start":1225.744,"stop":1228.591,"duration":2.85}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well yes, to accept money --","start":1228.591,"stop":1230.916,"duration":2.33}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Where is that printed?","start":1230.916,"stop":1232.149,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"It's 18 U.S.C 205.","start":1232.149,"stop":1234.051,"duration":1.9},{"text":"It's not in our brief.","start":1234.051,"stop":1236.147,"duration":2.1},{"text":"We have 281 but we don't have 205.","start":1236.147,"stop":1239.114,"duration":2.97},{"text":"But, in our reply brief, oh, in our required brief, Your Honor --","start":1239.114,"stop":1244.631,"duration":5.52}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that a general statute so we can go into that influence or did it specifically say that he accepted the money for making the speech, he'd be guilty about it--","start":1244.631,"stop":1252.01,"duration":7.38}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it doesn't say speech, what it says is it's in our reply brief on the footnote four on page seven it says, -- it provided for the punishment of any Congressman who agrees to receive money and now I'm quoting, “with the intent to have his action and so or the decision influence in any question, matter, cause or proceeding, which may, at anytime depending in either House of Congress or before any committee; thereof or which by law maybe brought before him in his capacity as such member.”","start":1252.01,"stop":1300.434,"duration":48.42}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That means that if he agrees for money, knowingly to accept that money for the purpose of doing what he's going to do in bad faith, doesn't it?","start":1300.434,"stop":1317.321,"duration":16.89}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"What means is he does it for money.","start":1317.321,"stop":1319.435,"duration":2.11}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1319.435,"stop":1320.141,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"It's the same as if he voted for a bill.","start":1320.141,"stop":1323.268,"duration":3.13},{"text":"I think the situation is no different that if he took $500.00 to vote yes on a bill.","start":1323.268,"stop":1327.107,"duration":3.84}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Bribed in to vote for a bill?","start":1327.107,"stop":1329.151,"duration":2.04}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1329.151,"stop":1330.996,"duration":1.85},{"text":"And, in the Manson case, which was a present judicial case, an argument was made, well, nobody shown that the judges' decision was wrong and, the Second Circuit says, “No, nobody has.”","start":1330.996,"stop":1344.163,"duration":13.17},{"text":"As a matter of fact, proof indicates that he made a decision that he thought was probably right, but the fact that he did it for money, and not honestly, and to take the real purpose --","start":1344.163,"stop":1355.829,"duration":11.67}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Was any charge here that he did not honestly believe what he said, that's what I'm getting here.","start":1355.829,"stop":1361.54,"duration":5.71}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"That was not part of the government's case.","start":1361.54,"stop":1364.126,"duration":2.59},{"text":"I think there was -- there was on course examination.","start":1364.126,"stop":1370.829,"duration":6.7},{"text":"They brought out facts which one could read this -- that someone could reach this conclusion, but it was not.","start":1370.829,"stop":1378.578,"duration":7.75},{"text":"The government did not rest on that as part of its case, no.","start":1378.578,"stop":1382.71,"duration":4.13},{"text":"The theory of robbery statutes quite generally, as I understand it is, that if you take money to influence official action, this is true any parties, judges, prosecutors, executives, you take money to influence official action, that's a crime.","start":1382.71,"stop":1403.953,"duration":21.24}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Miss Rosenberg can you read 281 as applying to proceedings in the Congress or before a committee of Congress?","start":1403.953,"stop":1413.793,"duration":9.84}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1413.793,"stop":1415.103,"duration":1.31},{"text":"There's a mistake Your Honor.","start":1415.103,"stop":1417.386,"duration":2.28},{"text":"I -- 205 was not factored in our brief.","start":1417.386,"stop":1421.169,"duration":3.78},{"text":"281 referred -- this thing you have to remember that this case dealt with two aspects, the conspiracy charge with two aspects, and all the substantive counts on the 281 where in the 281 made up with the representations before the Department of Justice.","start":1421.169,"stop":1436.979,"duration":15.81}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what I thought, yes.","start":1436.979,"stop":1438.561,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"And, somehow, 205 just didn't get cited in our brief its former 205.","start":1438.561,"stop":1446.02,"duration":7.46},{"text":"The 201, 281 and 205 are both now incorporated in 201, which is the conflict of interest statute.","start":1446.02,"stop":1457.271,"duration":11.25},{"text":"It was reenacted in 1962, which the day after the crime here.","start":1457.271,"stop":1464.462,"duration":7.19}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what statute am I supposed to be looking at?","start":1464.462,"stop":1467.419,"duration":2.96}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"205 18 U.S.C. 205 in the 1960 edition and the only precedent is quoted.","start":1467.419,"stop":1474.057,"duration":6.64}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"It's old 205.","start":1474.057,"stop":1475.608,"duration":1.55}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"That's old 205, and it's on page seven of our reply brief footnote four, the significant aspect.","start":1475.608,"stop":1481.908,"duration":6.3},{"text":"Note as I say this wasn't charged directly under 205 let me make this clear.","start":1481.908,"stop":1486.017,"duration":4.11}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1486.017,"stop":1486.676,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"This was charged as the conspiracy to defraud to the United States because it was in two aspects.","start":1486.676,"stop":1493.35,"duration":6.67},{"text":"It was to [Inaudible] the United States to the good services of the Congressman and as a matter of fact, my opponent makes a big issue of that.","start":1493.35,"stop":1502.099,"duration":8.75},{"text":"But, this is the way it was done in Manson, it was done in Black, it was done May.","start":1502.099,"stop":1509.103,"duration":7},{"text":"It is normally done that way where you have a continuing conspiracy with several aspects because this was, the basic charge here was that he was bought to use the vernacular, to use his Congressional influence for his two co-conspirators and his Congressional influence was used in several ways one of which was, to make the speech and the other was, to bring his influence to bear on the Department of Justice.","start":1509.103,"stop":1542.233,"duration":33.13}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But what you are saying in final analysis it gets to that, doesn't it, the fact assuming that he made it in the probability to say it.","start":1542.233,"stop":1550.658,"duration":8.42},{"text":"But, then he violated the law was making the speech, for which he took money but you have to have the speech in it and assume that best thing to make a speech in favor of various thoughts, doesn't it?","start":1550.658,"stop":1563.68,"duration":13.02}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"No your Honor, I think, you have different [Inaudible]","start":1563.68,"stop":1564.863,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And, then you're here.","start":1564.863,"stop":1566.292,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"We view with differently -- we view with what was bad was taking the money and it was taking the money to influence his official action it was doing something for money, whether he would have done it otherwise or not is immaterial.","start":1566.292,"stop":1582.787,"duration":16.5},{"text":"And, this can't fine true or not that the whole temptation of bribery law is for the whole purposes of free Speech and Debate Clause and the purposes of that the privilege is then recognizing so as to say we want people to exercise their best judgment.","start":1582.787,"stop":1599.341,"duration":16.55},{"text":"And, particularly, in the Speech and Debate Cause, the reason the Congressman are protected is that we want them to be able to speak for the whole people, for their constituents without fear and so on, but when somebody dissenting for money is exact opposite of the purpose of the Speech and Debate Clause.","start":1599.341,"stop":1618.816,"duration":19.48}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean he may go ahead and doing what would be their duty otherwise to make the speech in favor of something they're far.","start":1618.816,"stop":1624.915,"duration":6.1},{"text":"You say if they get some money for it, that's a crime.","start":1624.915,"stop":1628.206,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes Your Honor.","start":1628.206,"stop":1629.167,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But, you have to draw that from very language.","start":1629.167,"stop":1631.455,"duration":2.29},{"text":"I should think that that's to be made a crime, honestly, to make the speech in order to be in pretty clear language.","start":1631.455,"stop":1638.288,"duration":6.83}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I can't -- they think I -- then, the legislative history shows that back in 1862, the Congressman thought they said it was as comprehensive as a man could make it or something of that sort.","start":1638.288,"stop":1650.293,"duration":12}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Sometimes, they are so comprehensive if they don't have the --","start":1650.293,"stop":1653.984,"duration":3.69}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"But, I'd -- I see – I don't see for at that any different from any of the situation, you are private juror, it perfectly possible the juror might vote into [Inaudible]","start":1653.984,"stop":1663.4,"duration":9.42}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Then, I would have to vote, that's right.","start":1663.4,"stop":1668.925,"duration":5.52}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1668.925,"stop":1669.426,"duration":0.5},{"text":"It perfectly possibly might have acquitted anyway as I say we have a situation of Judge Madden who probably would have rendered the same decisions anyway one might have.","start":1669.426,"stop":1680.181,"duration":10.76}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But, there was no -- there was no constitutional provision that permitted Judge Madden to say what he say -- said to that at that time.","start":1680.181,"stop":1689.271,"duration":9.09},{"text":"There is a constitutional provision which permits the Congressman to make the speech or senator and it can't be -- and nothing could be done to him for it?","start":1689.271,"stop":1699.017,"duration":9.75},{"text":"You can't base it on what he said in making the speech, can you?","start":1699.017,"stop":1702.711,"duration":3.69}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"No, you can't, base it on what he said in the speech but then-- when couldn't--","start":1702.711,"stop":1706.685,"duration":3.97}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And yet it was the same [Inaudible]","start":1706.685,"stop":1707.694,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"When he have done anything to judgment and for what he said as an opinion.","start":1707.694,"stop":1710.198,"duration":2.5},{"text":"It might have been much worse and what he said --","start":1710.198,"stop":1711.835,"duration":1.64}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"It's essential to the conviction is that he made a speech in the Congress.","start":1711.835,"stop":1716.871,"duration":5.04}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it isn't.","start":1716.871,"stop":1717.476,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Where frequently people is not essential?","start":1717.476,"stop":1719.716,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"No, suppose if -- this -- as I say it, I said at the beginning, if we have a situation where he took money to make a speech and never made the speech, if he was to prove it and at sometimes one can, there have been such situation, not with the Congressman but with --","start":1719.716,"stop":1733.749,"duration":14.03}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you got to do the -- could you make your case without introducing the speech?","start":1733.749,"stop":1741.296,"duration":7.55}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean without introducing the reprints?","start":1741.296,"stop":1745.504,"duration":4.21}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Over that --","start":1745.504,"stop":1745.984,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"I would --","start":1745.984,"stop":1746.569,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Over that I was I referring to the fact that he had made the speech?","start":1746.569,"stop":1750.792,"duration":4.22}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I think not.","start":1750.792,"stop":1751.757,"duration":0.97},{"text":"I think we have to refer to the fact that he made a speech but we do not have -- we did not have to do this.","start":1751.757,"stop":1757.011,"duration":5.25}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Impugn in the contents?","start":1757.011,"stop":1758.108,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"We did not have to prove the content and as I say the contents that we did prove, there's no question, we did introduce the reprint, but the contents that we did introduce were the reprints and the reprints were at least so far as the type of what's concerned and the significant part, significantly different, the type of it was different, the rest of the speech was [Inaudible] except that when the [Inaudible] is sent it out, they undermined it in red.","start":1758.108,"stop":1787.265,"duration":29.16},{"text":"But, I think it's very different situation because I think the whole point is that the Speech and Debate Clause is out to protect the contents of the speech.","start":1787.265,"stop":1796.929,"duration":9.66},{"text":"And, if you look at every case in which the Speech and Debate Clause has been discussed.","start":1796.929,"stop":1801.782,"duration":4.85},{"text":"As I said before, you have a situation where the content of the speech are the foundation of the action, because it is the content which give you the injury.","start":1801.782,"stop":1813.458,"duration":11.68}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'll come back to my other question it's interesting that you [Voice Overlap] speech was called was in your [Inaudible] impugn the veracity of it that they have.","start":1813.458,"stop":1826.26,"duration":12.8},{"text":"When you make your prior good [Inaudible] aren't necessarily drawing in question the good faith of the speech in the public –","start":1826.26,"stop":1836.34,"duration":10.08}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think you're doing the good faith in the speech into question anymore than you are the good faith of the decision.","start":1836.34,"stop":1843,"duration":6.66},{"text":"If you say that --","start":1843,"stop":1843.903,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, is to that to the show that money was handed to some judge to make the decision to --","start":1843.903,"stop":1850.751,"duration":6.85}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, when you impugn a speech but that isn't what the Speech and Debate Clause, I don't think -- but the Speech and Debate Clause without to protect was the right of a Congressman.","start":1850.751,"stop":1863.227,"duration":12.48}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I think all of the question and then the other [Inaudible]","start":1863.227,"stop":1866.766,"duration":3.54}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it is questioned on what he said, that you should not question what he said.","start":1866.766,"stop":1874.114,"duration":7.35},{"text":"I think that's what the Speech or Debate Clause means.","start":1874.114,"stop":1878.055,"duration":3.94},{"text":"That you shall not question what was done, I think, because it is possible this time -- this Court said in the Time case [Inaudible] could have been into the heat of the debate but you can't say he made a mistake and he injured me and therefore, he has to be liable.","start":1878.055,"stop":1902.066,"duration":24.01}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Miss Rosenberg, I'd like to ask you help me out.","start":1902.066,"stop":1907.955,"duration":5.89},{"text":"As I understand and what you have is charge of a conspiracy.","start":1907.955,"stop":1911.969,"duration":4.01}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1911.969,"stop":1912.24,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"And you have just dissent that in order to make it true, you have to use the fact that the Congressman made a speech.","start":1912.24,"stop":1925.205,"duration":12.96},{"text":"That is what your stand upon --","start":1925.205,"stop":1926.024,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we did, I mean whether it's hard to say.","start":1926.024,"stop":1929.995,"duration":3.97},{"text":"There was a question preliminary evidence but I suppose -- I -- we certainly did prove that he made the speech.","start":1929.995,"stop":1937.868,"duration":7.87},{"text":"We proved to the public relations made.","start":1937.868,"stop":1941.222,"duration":3.35},{"text":"Maybe at this point, I should just summarize what our proof was.","start":1941.222,"stop":1944.627,"duration":3.4}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if you permit me to ask you my question.","start":1944.627,"stop":1946.733,"duration":2.11}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry.","start":1946.733,"stop":1947.404,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"If you don't mind.","start":1947.404,"stop":1949.126,"duration":1.72},{"text":"Now, would you agree that if the Government has filed it's proof of conspiracy and used the text of the speech and had gone into the substance of the speech, would you or would you not feel that that's -- would be a violation of the constitutional [Inaudible]","start":1949.126,"stop":1978.356,"duration":29.23}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I think -- I think the Government could not base its affirmative case of the cons -- on the content of the speech.","start":1978.356,"stop":1984.894,"duration":6.54}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, he has us told us earlier, if I correctly remember, that the Government did use a substance of the speech in the cross examination of Congressman Johnson?","start":1984.894,"stop":1996.84,"duration":11.95}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1996.84,"stop":1997.64,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"So that, is this -- does this case present essentially on your view of it a question of degree, that is to say whether the Government used the speech or went in to the speech in such a degree to such amount or for such a purposes or how do you want to phrase it, as to violate the constitutional immunity?","start":1997.64,"stop":2026.441,"duration":28.8}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let me say that I think as the Court here that is as decided by the Court of Appeals, no because the Court of Appeals decided it very broadly.","start":2026.441,"stop":2038.835,"duration":12.39},{"text":"They decided that any prosecution for bribery was barred by the Speech and Debate Clause.","start":2038.835,"stop":2047.062,"duration":8.23},{"text":"And now, obviously, if that is decided again differently from the way the Court of Appeals decided it and it is possible and the Court holds that there can be prosecutions for bribery, then it begs to the question of, “Is this prosecution?”","start":2047.062,"stop":2068.563,"duration":21.5}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"There is sometimes -- sometimes, this Court as I understand [Inaudible] things the other way around.","start":2068.563,"stop":2074.719,"duration":6.16}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, except that the Court of Appeals never did decide mostly that if it can't involve too much use of the speech.","start":2074.719,"stop":2089.089,"duration":14.37},{"text":"What the Court of Appeals said was no speech.","start":2089.089,"stop":2093.974,"duration":4.89},{"text":"The minute you have a prosecution for bribery to make a speech that outlawed.","start":2093.974,"stop":2099.805,"duration":5.83},{"text":"Now, the question of whether I think that decision would be made on the book firmly can't be affirmed obviously on different grounds, but I think that the decision has rendered us prevent the broader question.","start":2099.805,"stop":2118.504,"duration":18.7},{"text":"Now, there is involved in that a narrower question of whether too much use was made of the speech here and that just brings me to the question of what we proved in this case.","start":2118.504,"stop":2130.689,"duration":12.18},{"text":"What we showed was, that Edlin and one of his companies was under indictment and interested in getting what one might call a federal public image so they hired a public relations man named Edlin and, they talked about having a speech made in April in May of 1960.","start":2130.689,"stop":2156.811,"duration":26.12},{"text":"The speech that they prepared -- this is what the government's affirmative case showed obviously contemplated the speech in the House of Representatives.","start":2156.811,"stop":2165.248,"duration":8.44},{"text":"The draft -- they were preparing draft to the speech because references were put in to a Mister Speaker.","start":2165.248,"stop":2175.088,"duration":9.84}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"To of what?","start":2175.088,"stop":2175.948,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Speaker, indicating that they expected it to be given in the House of Representatives.","start":2175.948,"stop":2180.625,"duration":4.68},{"text":"This was the draft.","start":2180.625,"stop":2182.447,"duration":1.82},{"text":"In May, at a luncheon with respondent, Edlin and the public relations man discussed in general, the plight of the of the so called independent Maryland Savings and Loan institution, as I say one of which whom was under indictment.","start":2182.447,"stop":2200.913,"duration":18.47},{"text":"Sometime in May, it doesn't appear exactly when in relation to this luncheon with respondent, Heflin told Edlin that there was no time limit in the speech, no reason to make it.","start":2200.913,"stop":2217.285,"duration":16.37},{"text":"However, on May 27, 1963, there was this jury in the financial pages of the Washington's jar which called the Maryland Savings and Loan Associations phoney.","start":2217.285,"stop":2235.056,"duration":17.77}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Called it what?","start":2235.056,"stop":2235.848,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Phoney.","start":2235.848,"stop":2238.211,"duration":2.36},{"text":"After that Heflin and Edlin's attorney, who was the defendant Robinson went to the respondent's office and they discussed the star article with him and showed him these drafts -- the draft that they had prepared.","start":2238.211,"stop":2255.925,"duration":17.71},{"text":"Robinson said his administrative assistant would go over the material I mean respond that his administrative assistant would go over the material.","start":2255.925,"stop":2266.141,"duration":10.22},{"text":"Subsequently, Heflin as a public relations man, supplied facts and figures and the administrative assistant sent him a draft.","start":2266.141,"stop":2278.111,"duration":11.97},{"text":"Heflin learned about the speech about two days after it was given and issued a press release based on the speech.","start":2278.111,"stop":2288.034,"duration":9.92},{"text":"Edlin issued fifty thousand reprints for his company and the marked parts have them in red and sent them out in answers to people wrote in about the Maryland Savings and Loan Association.","start":2288.034,"stop":2306.562,"duration":18.53},{"text":"It's about this time they started – they reactivated the second of this company which should have been dormant until then called Red Continental and they sent out in the answers to inquiries about the institution, copies of the speech with underlining in red.","start":2306.562,"stop":2326.495,"duration":19.93},{"text":"As I said before, the only copies of the speech which the Government introduced in this direct case was one of these reprints which had a very different kind of a heading -- a much more dramatic heading about the federal savings and loans seeking destruction of the Independent.","start":2326.495,"stop":2347.5,"duration":21.01}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now what -- to what issue was that offer of proof relevant?","start":2347.5,"stop":2352.379,"duration":4.88}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"All this was relevant as bearing on the question of the Congressman taking money to work in the interest -- in the Edlin interest first, to make a speech and then, to bring pressure on the Department of Justice.","start":2352.379,"stop":2370.663,"duration":18.28}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that it -- you've emphasized twice that they made a difference in caption.","start":2370.663,"stop":2375.459,"duration":4.8},{"text":"What was the significance of that on -- has bearing on the issue in the case?","start":2375.459,"stop":2382.977,"duration":7.52}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh!","start":2382.977,"stop":2383.169,"duration":0.19},{"text":"It shows that it was done, I think hence, to prove that it was done for, besides [Inaudible] any other money [Inaudible]","start":2383.169,"stop":2391.634,"duration":8.47}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well then so that extends at least the Government's case rested on the speech, at least the caption of it.","start":2391.634,"stop":2397.462,"duration":5.83}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"But, the caption was not the caption of the speech.","start":2397.462,"stop":2400.66,"duration":3.2},{"text":"The caption put on the speech was not the caption of the speech as is reported in the Congressional record.","start":2400.66,"stop":2407.41,"duration":6.75}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you drawing the distinction that if you use a copy of the speech with reference to the clerk, will bring it to the Congressional record that that might have defended the constitution of protection, is that what you're saying?","start":2407.41,"stop":2422.621,"duration":15.21}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it tends to prove to that, I think it is a fact that we did not rely on the speech as given its part of the affirmative play.","start":2422.621,"stop":2433.827,"duration":11.21},{"text":"It shows that it was one of the circumstances that indicate that this was part of the conspiracy that this was prepared that the speech was given for money, for the interest of the defendant, of the co-defendant, the co-conspirators who gave the money and on the money question --","start":2433.827,"stop":2460.107,"duration":26.28}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Was he convicted for conclusion of the fraud generally or just the conspiracy case, defraud the government, this man.","start":2460.107,"stop":2469.442,"duration":9.34}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the charge with conspiracy to defraud the United States of the good offices of the Congressman and --","start":2469.442,"stop":2475.717,"duration":6.28}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"So what was the charge against the other -- others, I should say.","start":2475.717,"stop":2478.379,"duration":2.66}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think that they all conspired to defraud the United States of the honest services of the Congressman, of the honest services of the Department of Justice and --","start":2478.379,"stop":2491.648,"duration":13.27}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"The same charge against all.","start":2491.648,"stop":2493.153,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it was on the conspiracy charge.","start":2493.153,"stop":2495,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2495,"stop":2495.682,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"On the other separate counter charge here the others would charge if they're to admit that to be put as a violation --","start":2495.682,"stop":2502.968,"duration":7.29}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Was he tried for the other two?","start":2502.968,"stop":2504.667,"duration":1.7}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2504.667,"stop":2505.455,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Was he convicted?","start":2505.455,"stop":2506.33,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"He was convicted.","start":2506.33,"stop":2507.488,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"On that too?","start":2507.488,"stop":2509.055,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"He was convicted of the substantive count and the only reason the Court of Appeals reversed that was that they thought maybe the evidence as to the speech had a bearing on the conviction of the other count.","start":2509.055,"stop":2525.41,"duration":16.36},{"text":"I think when we in the record might be in the other way when we could have read it, had come to another conclusion but we have not brought that issue here.","start":2525.41,"stop":2533.952,"duration":8.54}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course the other counts have noting to do with the speech?","start":2533.952,"stop":2536.305,"duration":2.35}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"No, this count had nothing to do with the issue.","start":2536.305,"stop":2537.661,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And then they would apparently were --","start":2537.661,"stop":2540.298,"duration":2.64}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2540.298,"stop":2542.277,"duration":1.98},{"text":"But they were reversed because of the speech issue.","start":2542.277,"stop":2548.679,"duration":6.4},{"text":"Now on the question of the money what was shown was that ten days before the speech was given, respondent received $500.","start":2548.679,"stop":2562.584,"duration":13.9},{"text":"This wasn't given directly.","start":2562.584,"stop":2567.624,"duration":5.04},{"text":"It was a check sent by Robinson who was the attorney and who lived in Florida, and it was sent to respondent.","start":2567.624,"stop":2575.861,"duration":8.24},{"text":"Now he endorsed it over to his campaign treasurer that came in the government's case.","start":2575.861,"stop":2582.548,"duration":6.69},{"text":"Subsequently, in August respondent received a $1,000 check from Robinson for which Robinson was reimbursed by ones of savings and loan institutions that was marked of legal services.","start":2582.548,"stop":2599.678,"duration":17.13},{"text":"In November there was a $300 check to a campaign treasurer again from Robinson in Florida for which Robinson was again reimbursed this time [Inaudible] by Continental and then starting in January 1961 there were four checks for $800 and then from March to October and it was March to October when the representation to the Department of Justice were made, it was about $20,000 all paid through Robinson and to the defendant like the government also show as part of it's affirmative case was that there were no legal services rendered for this money.","start":2599.678,"stop":2660.763,"duration":61.09},{"text":"The proof of that became even stronger as the respondent had testified and so if you read the opinion a good deal of that proof does referred to the testimony of the respondent but the government did show affirmative proof in that direction.","start":2660.763,"stop":2683.384,"duration":22.62},{"text":"Now it's therefore evident that the government did not rely on the content of the speech at all to prove this case.","start":2683.384,"stop":2692.623,"duration":9.24},{"text":"It did prove that speech was given.","start":2692.623,"stop":2696.735,"duration":4.11},{"text":"It did prove that the speech was useful and was used by it's -- the co-conspirators.","start":2696.735,"stop":2707.544,"duration":10.81},{"text":"It did prove that money went from the co-conspirators to respondent and did prove that he did not render services which would justify that money and that was the government has.","start":2707.544,"stop":2724.159,"duration":16.62},{"text":"Now when respondents got up he did that or I think I should say one other thing it doesn't show up in the appendix but there isn't a [Inaudible] evidence that reporter from the Washington Post talked to respondents in December 1961 which is before the they were given any action both about representations before the Department of Justice and the representation and the speech.","start":2724.159,"stop":2760.282,"duration":36.12},{"text":"And the government affirmatively did put on that reporter who said that respondent told him in 1961 that he made the speech because the constituents asked.","start":2760.282,"stop":2773.499,"duration":13.22}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"To -- another what?","start":2773.499,"stop":2775.029,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Because the constituent asked it.","start":2775.029,"stop":2782.212,"duration":7.18},{"text":"As I said that wasn't reprinted in the appendix but it is in the record.","start":2782.212,"stop":2787.135,"duration":4.92},{"text":"Now when respondent took the stand he did say that he gave a speech because he thought it would make a good campaign issue and the government of course examined him about that.","start":2787.135,"stop":2799.45,"duration":12.31}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask you Ms. Rosenberg, on the government's direct case I take that the defense objected though the evidence about the speech, on the government's direct case.","start":2799.45,"stop":2810.873,"duration":11.42}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well they had made a motion to dismiss before trial on the ground that the indictment of the Court by the Speech and Debate Clause.","start":2810.873,"stop":2825.176,"duration":14.3}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But what about objections to this --","start":2825.176,"stop":2826.648,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't -- and it had been overruled by the district judge who said that it didn't do it.","start":2826.648,"stop":2832.743,"duration":6.09},{"text":"I don't recall that every time any piece of evidence came in specifically on that that they made that objection in those terms.","start":2832.743,"stop":2842.608,"duration":9.87},{"text":"There were various objections in the Court held that other things questions about why they went further into the conspiracy --","start":2842.608,"stop":2848.052,"duration":5.44}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Was there a motion for acquittal at the government's case?","start":2848.052,"stop":2850.152,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, there was in motion for acquittal at the --","start":2850.152,"stop":2851.616,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Did that rest on the Speech and Debate Clause in the part?","start":2851.616,"stop":2856.005,"duration":4.39}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think he renewed the motion before trial and I think that -- I don't think that they were focused narrowly on the fact that too much use was made of the speech as such.","start":2856.005,"stop":2868.087,"duration":12.08},{"text":"It was generally, there is no question that consistently the defendant has argued by motion to dismiss the motion for acquittal and so on that the whole constitution was [Inaudible]","start":2868.087,"stop":2878.249,"duration":10.16}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So the government makes no point of any failure to object to those --","start":2878.249,"stop":2881.479,"duration":3.23}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2881.479,"stop":2881.886,"duration":0.41},{"text":"He's raised that point consistently but as I say one of the problems is that to where this has been approached broadly, it's been approached as if there is prosecution is possible or is it not and I don't think at any stage really there has been any sharp vote that it's been mentioned that the defendant uses it in support of his argument and we did talk about in our main brief but there has not been any sharp purpose on the narrow question of --","start":2881.886,"stop":2919.335,"duration":37.45}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Hadn't been any, what?","start":2919.335,"stop":2920.256,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Sharp protest on the narrow question of whether in this particular trial there was reliance or too much reliance on the contents of the speech.","start":2920.256,"stop":2931.783,"duration":11.53}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What would you think about [Inaudible], provided that it should be a crime people to get together and agree among themselves to urge a campaign, to do everything possible, they get Congressman to make speeches on the bill.","start":2931.783,"stop":2954.056,"duration":22.27},{"text":"Could that's be permissible --","start":2954.056,"stop":2955.713,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that would be a permissible --","start":2955.713,"stop":2956.648,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think that would be --","start":2956.648,"stop":2957.942,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"That's just urging it.","start":2957.942,"stop":2959.31,"duration":1.37},{"text":"That's very different it seems to me from buying somebody.","start":2959.31,"stop":2962.187,"duration":2.88}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, suppose they have said that they're going to try to get it done if necessary.","start":2962.187,"stop":2966.463,"duration":4.28},{"text":"They had paid for the speech as [Inaudible] that they're going to do extra work, what about the right to petition?","start":2966.463,"stop":2977.272,"duration":10.81}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"They have a right to petition but they don't have the right to bribe.","start":2977.272,"stop":2979.837,"duration":2.57}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand but bribe means many different things you can give a word of that conduct of bad name.","start":2979.837,"stop":2986.555,"duration":6.72}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it's bad.","start":2986.555,"stop":2987.35,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"We had a case that long ago of Noah against somebody and which is -- a railroad, they tried everywhere in the world to get enough money and so forth to keep laws from being passed one way or another and [Inaudible] promulgating and we know that they can bring their turn for that.","start":2987.35,"stop":3008.285,"duration":20.93}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"What we do have Your Honor has it and the Court has upheld that, the people who lobby have to register so that there is and I think --","start":3008.285,"stop":3019.323,"duration":11.04}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But registering is quite different from outlawing it.","start":3019.323,"stop":3023.5,"duration":4.18}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that there's a big difference also from saying that one may raise money and petition and request a Congressman or any interested economic group has the right to bring [Inaudible]","start":3023.5,"stop":3041.893,"duration":18.39}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And hire people, hire people to go and lobby with the Congressman --","start":3041.893,"stop":3045.632,"duration":3.74}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, but I think it is very different situation where and in the sense empathetical to the whole idea that of the right to petition where you have somebody passing money surreptitiously under the table.","start":3045.632,"stop":3066.367,"duration":20.74},{"text":"I think its exactly then and the feeling that Congressman do something not because of whatever legitimate political pressures do but for money this is a --","start":3066.367,"stop":3081.836,"duration":15.47}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose that's been get up for fund, I think I have heard of that being done, they get into the corner, they help the Congressman or a senator in connection with his campaigns and things and they want legislation passed and they go to them and asking to get it passed, would that -- that be made a crime?","start":3081.836,"stop":3104.891,"duration":23.06}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Because that's their right to petition.","start":3104.891,"stop":3107.707,"duration":2.82},{"text":"But this is bringing not a normal political pressure but the pressures of money to bear in a sense to divert the normal political pressures.","start":3107.707,"stop":3122.033,"duration":14.33}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it -- as I understand, suppose this man had been fighting for this bill a long time, he's [Inaudible] it's been his bill he knows and to people who also thought that the -- you make some speeches on it.","start":3122.033,"stop":3136.296,"duration":14.26},{"text":"He says “Well I -- I can't spend no --” and they say “We'll give you some money to make a speech.”","start":3136.296,"stop":3144.992,"duration":8.7},{"text":"You'd say that that could be a crime?","start":3144.992,"stop":3147.503,"duration":2.51}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"I said that the Congress could make this for him.","start":3147.503,"stop":3148.555,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You'd know his problem and [Inaudible] I am going to do everything I can for him, they want to stimulate him with what they called something a bonus let's say, so if he could -- he use different --","start":3148.555,"stop":3162.022,"duration":13.47}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"I think the Congress has to right that we don't want bonuses and I think the Congress had done so. The Congress has done it since 1853.","start":3162.022,"stop":3170.802,"duration":8.78},{"text":"It has the bribery statute on the Congress if then so --","start":3170.802,"stop":3173.033,"duration":2.23}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well it would be quite a different statute wouldn't it, if it said that no Congressman to accept employment the minute of the service while using Congress.","start":3173.033,"stop":3182.389,"duration":9.36}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, the constitution said that, but -- well, as in the Executive Department and then they do say the Congressman can't do certain type of things in their private employment but the Congress has also said and they said it since 1853.","start":3182.389,"stop":3201.616,"duration":19.23},{"text":"Every legislature I think of every state the union had said it, we don't want Congressman voting or making speeches for money.","start":3201.616,"stop":3214.314,"duration":12.7}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And now there's a difference between voting and making speeches, doesn't it?","start":3214.314,"stop":3217.409,"duration":3.1}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think so.","start":3217.409,"stop":3218.065,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That the Constitution says something about making speeches.","start":3218.065,"stop":3222.037,"duration":3.97}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that this Court said since the time Kilbourn against Thompson that the Speech or Debate Clause includes voting.","start":3222.037,"stop":3227.742,"duration":5.71}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"A what?","start":3227.742,"stop":3229.026,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"That the Speech or Debate Clause in encompasses voting as well as future debate.","start":3229.026,"stop":3234.914,"duration":5.89},{"text":"That's been decided in Kilbourn against Thompson and I think and since the old Massachusetts case that this Court had cited in Tenney, Coffin against Coffin before Massachusetts.","start":3234.914,"stop":3247.384,"duration":12.47}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"The statute shows action or voting?","start":3247.384,"stop":3250.343,"duration":2.96}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"The statute says the action on any matter pending but I don't think the fact -- now in the Massachusetts bribery statute for instance specifically mentioned speech but to say that a matter is within the Speech and Debate Clause and then its not within this comprehensive bribery statute it seems to me very inconsistent.","start":3250.343,"stop":3274.61,"duration":24.27},{"text":"I think the fact is that I have -- it vote, it's within the Speech and Debate Clause and it -- had so been interpreted by this Court from the beginning then there is no constitutional difference between speech or vote and something -- there are all kinds of actions that it done we have it right down the line.","start":3274.61,"stop":3305.467,"duration":30.86},{"text":"All kinds of action which cannot be questioned in the sense that you can't show that its bad judgment or that it was done from [Inaudible].","start":3305.467,"stop":3318.609,"duration":13.14},{"text":"You have it as to prosecutors, the Courts stated they have -- you can't sue them making their judgment and from now it's -- you have it as the judge, you have it as the Congressman.","start":3318.609,"stop":3331.106,"duration":12.5}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Ms. Rosenberg suppose that a Congressman get up and [Inaudible] with the Congress says, “I want all of you to know that I am a member of the communist party and I believe an overthrow of this government by force and violence.”","start":3331.106,"stop":3346.734,"duration":15.63},{"text":"Could he be prosecuted under the membership clause that was provided?","start":3346.734,"stop":3351.24,"duration":4.51},{"text":"Suppose he got a $1,000 for making that statement?","start":3351.24,"stop":3354.244,"duration":3}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"That's different because then he's being prosecuted for taking a $1,000 to make it.","start":3354.244,"stop":3360.551,"duration":6.31},{"text":"I don't think that's there's any difference in saying that a juror votes to acquit because he likes people with red hair and that's -- that there's nothing anybody can do about it.","start":3360.551,"stop":3372.096,"duration":11.55},{"text":"They vote.","start":3372.096,"stop":3375.085,"duration":2.99},{"text":"But if a juror vote to acquit because somebody gave him a $1,000 can prosecuted, and exactly this comes within the Speech and Debate Clause but that principle doesn't seem to me any different.","start":3375.085,"stop":3387.671,"duration":12.59},{"text":"It doesn't seem to me any different if you say this is a perfectly sound accusation which would stand up in any appellant court and which this Court would affirm but you can't give it for -- you can't take a $1,000 to give it.","start":3387.671,"stop":3401.354,"duration":13.68},{"text":"I think that for the purposes of what constitutes questioning there is no essential difference between the judicial privilege and the -- there's never been question that you can't have people going around bribing jurors, bribing judges.","start":3401.354,"stop":3419.073,"duration":17.72},{"text":"And I don't think why it should be different for Congressman and the point is not what I think, the point is that the Congress had not thought should be a different proponent.","start":3419.073,"stop":3428.794,"duration":9.72}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, has the Congress said it would reference to a man's speech, it was raised by the different question with me, the founders have said that I don't --","start":3428.794,"stop":3438.488,"duration":9.69}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, then your question is a very narrow one which is when former 205 which was passed in 1862, the Congressman on the board said “This is a comprehensive legislation that we know how to do it.”","start":3438.488,"stop":3461.32,"duration":22.83},{"text":"That's what they said about it at that time.","start":3461.32,"stop":3464.077,"duration":2.76},{"text":"It does not in so many words use speech but it uses what they thought -- well I think comprehensively with what the Congress thought was comprehensive language.","start":3464.077,"stop":3477.088,"duration":13.01},{"text":"And the --","start":3477.088,"stop":3478.382,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What would they have to a particular that as I recall it they went up to a lot of people who [Inaudible] the Congress.","start":3478.382,"stop":3486.65,"duration":8.27}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"It was part of it that they certainly use -- they specifically used word action, action, to have it action vote or division influence.","start":3486.65,"stop":3497.611,"duration":10.96},{"text":"Now this is not to anyone, this is not the conflict of interstate, this is not dealing with what the Congress did as such.","start":3497.611,"stop":3509.506,"duration":11.89},{"text":"This is action brought or decision influenced on any question matter for or proceeding which may at anytime be pending in either House of Congress or before any committee thereof or which by law maybe brought before him in his capacity as such member, that's pretty broad language and it covers the right deal and all the state has similar statutes.","start":3509.506,"stop":3540.907,"duration":31.4}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll recess now.","start":3540.907,"stop":3550.599,"duration":9.69}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - November 15, 1965","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren13/oral_argument_audio/15115","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Johnson --","start":0,"stop":9.22,"duration":9.22}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice --","start":9.22,"stop":10.536,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Doub.","start":10.536,"stop":13.594,"duration":3.06}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"May the court please.","start":13.594,"stop":16.209,"duration":2.62},{"text":"Before discussing how the executive power unluckily violated in trespass upon the legislative liberty.","start":16.209,"stop":26.11,"duration":9.9},{"text":"In this case, I'm here to explain an important initial issue that really could be determinate here.","start":26.11,"stop":36.718,"duration":10.61},{"text":"The government did not charge Mr. Johnson with conspiring to violate any bribery statute.","start":36.718,"stop":48.297,"duration":11.58},{"text":"The government did not charge him with conspiring to violate any conflict of interest of the law.","start":48.297,"stop":58.012,"duration":9.72},{"text":"It didn't charge him in this first count that's conspiracy charge with conspiring to violate any substantive law of the United States.","start":58.012,"stop":72.885,"duration":14.87},{"text":"Thus, Section 205, the bribery statute which the government talked about a great deal was never involved in the trial of this case and was never, never before the jury.","start":72.885,"stop":94.273,"duration":21.39},{"text":"As a matter of fact, it wasn't even printed in a brief or either the government or for the defendant.","start":94.273,"stop":102.294,"duration":8.02}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think it would -– that would have been broad enough to include these acts?","start":102.294,"stop":106.36,"duration":4.07}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir?","start":106.36,"stop":107.243,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Would that have been broad enough to include these acts?","start":107.243,"stop":109.576,"duration":2.33},{"text":"I'm not asking you to pressure yourself on that point --","start":109.576,"stop":112.434,"duration":2.86}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm just coming to that later Mr. Justice Douglas.","start":112.434,"stop":117.444,"duration":5.01},{"text":"The bribery statute applies by its terms to the both---","start":117.444,"stop":124.638,"duration":7.19}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"That action too --","start":124.638,"stop":126.607,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Both action or decision I supposed.","start":126.607,"stop":129.269,"duration":2.66}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"I said conversing and speaking is a form of action.","start":129.269,"stop":134.025,"duration":4.76}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"We would say no, Your Honor.","start":134.025,"stop":135.976,"duration":1.95},{"text":"We would say that speech and debate was left out of that statute and could only be interpreted as -– in it was specifically mentioned in it.","start":135.976,"stop":150.761,"duration":14.78},{"text":"And also, that statute only applied to matters both decision or action with respect to matters pending in the Congress.","start":150.761,"stop":162.681,"duration":11.92},{"text":"In this case, Mr. Johnson's speech was unrelated to any matter pending in the Congress.","start":162.681,"stop":168.268,"duration":5.59}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that maybe an interview.","start":168.268,"stop":170.455,"duration":2.19}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What would that can be?","start":170.455,"stop":172.82,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir?","start":172.82,"stop":173.284,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What would you think action, the word action include?","start":173.284,"stop":177.716,"duration":4.43}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think it could include actions by committees of the Congress, appointments to committees, rulings by the presiding officer.","start":177.716,"stop":189.718,"duration":12},{"text":"All those things could be action.","start":189.718,"stop":192.3,"duration":2.58},{"text":"But could I come back to the --","start":192.3,"stop":194.648,"duration":2.35}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":194.648,"stop":201.662,"duration":7.01}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I think so.","start":201.662,"stop":203.398,"duration":1.74}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Doub, I understood you to say that there was no action of any kind of pending –- was there no investigation of savings and loan associations before the Congress at that time?","start":203.398,"stop":218.126,"duration":14.73}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"No, there were bills pending.","start":218.126,"stop":221.183,"duration":3.06}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I didn't asked if there were any bills pending I asked if there's any investigation or any companies interested in those sense?","start":221.183,"stop":228.608,"duration":7.43}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there's never been an reference to what by the government and there's never – I've never heard of any, there was never any reference in the trial of this case if there's --- there was never any claim by the government, let me put it that way.","start":228.608,"stop":243.768,"duration":15.16}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"I am just asking, I have no information on the side.","start":243.768,"stop":248.72,"duration":4.95}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Johnson was charged, was violating an 1867 conspiracy statute, making it an offense to conspire, to defraud the United States in any matter that was Section 371.","start":248.72,"stop":269.075,"duration":20.35},{"text":"So, the initial inquiry here is whether Congress in adopting that conspiracy statute intended that it should cover a conspiracy with respect to a speech in the House of Representative; preparation, source material, motivation, its causation and its publication.","start":269.075,"stop":303.738,"duration":34.66},{"text":"Now, this conspiracy statute was invalid in a tax bill in 1867 is considerable evidence that it was designed to meet much publicized tax fraud which preceded the introduction of this bill.","start":303.738,"stop":329.383,"duration":25.64},{"text":"But by reason of its general language, the judiciary quite properly held that it should apply to all frauds against the coin of contracts of the property of the United States because it said, conspiring to the fraud the United States in any manner.","start":329.383,"stop":357.628,"duration":28.25},{"text":"And that valid interpretation is reasonable and logical and it's been a great utility to the government.","start":357.628,"stop":365.172,"duration":7.54},{"text":"Then in 1910, in the Harris case, this court said, well, it meant more than that, it manifest conspiracy to defraud the United States by obstructing the efficiency of government operations and then in 1923, in the opinion by Chief Justice Taft he said, conspiracy to defraud the United States means primarily cheating the government out of its property or money but secondarily, as obstructing lawful, governmental functions deceit, dishonest means or overreaching.","start":365.172,"stop":418.596,"duration":53.42},{"text":"That stretched the statute for our behalf beyond anything known in the world of fraud extract it into the area of ethics, into the area of conflicts of interest.","start":418.596,"stop":435.246,"duration":16.65},{"text":"Because now the -– that was an unparalleled expansion of a penal statute.","start":435.246,"stop":442.519,"duration":7.27},{"text":"The obstruction of lawful, governmental functions of course has no real meaning; no meaning at all is a conspiracy to obstruct governmental functions by spending on the sidewalk in the District of Columbia.","start":442.519,"stop":458.484,"duration":15.96},{"text":"Is it conspiracy to obstruct governmental functions to agree with others to follow the war in Vietnam.","start":458.484,"stop":471.163,"duration":12.68},{"text":"This thing uses the word dishonest means an overreaching.","start":471.163,"stop":477.545,"duration":6.38},{"text":"Dishonest means an overreaching have anymore meaning in the law that's simple or wicked or unethical.","start":477.545,"stop":485.408,"duration":7.86}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"What is this Mr. Doub, vagueness argument, is this a vagueness argument?","start":485.408,"stop":487.841,"duration":2.43}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir?","start":487.841,"stop":488.222,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Is this a vagueness argument?","start":488.222,"stop":490.489,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I'm leading up to the fact that assuming that you accept this remarkable interpretation that hasn't been defended by single legal scholar in the country.","start":490.489,"stop":503.58,"duration":13.09},{"text":"Well, assuming if this court does say that's what the defrauding means, then we say that surely, you can stretch the accordion further and say that Congress intended to apply it to an alleged venal speech in the Congress.","start":503.58,"stop":529.847,"duration":26.27}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Is this an argument that what's charged here is not within the reach of the statute even as extended?","start":529.847,"stop":536.114,"duration":6.27}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":536.114,"stop":537.269,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"As though an alternate argument that if it is within the reach as so interpreted the statute void for vagueness.","start":537.269,"stop":543.748,"duration":6.48}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"You see the District Judge instructed this jury that this charge meant or Chief Justice Taft said it in Hammerschmidt.","start":543.748,"stop":558.278,"duration":14.53},{"text":"He said that the charge of violating the defrauding portion of this statute meant conspiracy to defraud the government by obstructing governmental functions by means which were dishonest or overreaching or chicanery and other appropriate words.","start":558.278,"stop":580.78,"duration":22.5},{"text":"So, to sustain count one, the initial issue is, did Congress in enacting that conspiracy statute intended, it should apply to a conspiracy with respect to speech?","start":580.78,"stop":598.997,"duration":18.22},{"text":"If Congress vital freedom of speech and debate to be at the mercy of a vague and imprecise, all inclusive charge under a general 1867 statute originally directed at frauds against the government's coin and property and even probably just taxes.","start":598.997,"stop":627.049,"duration":28.05},{"text":"Now, in turn you've thought us otherwise, there, members of a California Legislature which were alleged to have violated a civil conspiracy of law of 1871, as a matter of fact that law is more explicit far more than this vague indefinite catch all crime that Mr. Johnson was charged with under –- and you held the basic issue was whether Congress in enacting that statute intended to include within its coverage official acts of members of a legislature and you determine that Congress didn't have that intention.","start":627.049,"stop":674.381,"duration":47.33},{"text":"The court said this, did Congress by the general language of its 1871 statute mean to overturn the tradition of legislative freedom achieved in England by Civil War and carefully preserved in the formation of state and national governments here?","start":674.381,"stop":694.977,"duration":20.6},{"text":"Did it mean to subject legislatures to civil liability for acts done within the sphere of legislative activity?","start":694.977,"stop":702.666,"duration":7.69},{"text":"We can not believe that Congress is still (Inaudible) advocate of legislative freedom would impinge on a traditions by covered inclusion in the general language before us.","start":702.666,"stop":719.312,"duration":16.65}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"That was a –- not a constitutional decision was it?","start":719.312,"stop":723.219,"duration":3.91}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that decision was based on the fact --- that's right on the interpretation of a statute.","start":723.219,"stop":731.793,"duration":8.57},{"text":"And in other words along Article I Section 6 prefers to relate only the speech and debate in the Congress the court deemed this tradition of legislative freedom of such paramount importance it extended of all the official acts of members not only of Congress but in this case of a state legislature.","start":731.793,"stop":763.273,"duration":31.48},{"text":"This case doesn't relate to acts of the state legislature and our case doesn't even relate to official acts of a member of Congress unrelated to speech and debate.","start":763.273,"stop":774.211,"duration":10.94},{"text":"This case relates to the hardcore, that guts of the speech and debate provision, utterances on the floor of the chamber of the Congress and then motivation.","start":774.211,"stop":786.941,"duration":12.73}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think it would slowdown the public debate, if this indictment were upheld?","start":786.941,"stop":795.044,"duration":8.1}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it would be a disaster.","start":795.044,"stop":797.705,"duration":2.66},{"text":"I think it would be – I am coming to that but may I just finish --- I'd like to answer that in a moment.","start":797.705,"stop":804.75,"duration":7.04},{"text":"In Eastern Railroad conference case --","start":804.75,"stop":806.623,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"The reason I have that is the man is not being penalized for anything he says and --","start":806.623,"stop":813.697,"duration":7.07}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we think he was but may I come to that in a moment just let me finish --","start":813.697,"stop":818.234,"duration":4.54}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Maybe I just understood the facts, but I thought he was being punished here merely for getting money to make a certain speech.","start":818.234,"stop":826.455,"duration":8.22}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that's in the conspiracy charge.","start":826.455,"stop":829.655,"duration":3.2},{"text":"He collaborated with others in preparing a speech and then he was compensated for making the speech, through the hired speech and that he cooperated in the distribution and reprinting of that speech.","start":829.655,"stop":846.589,"duration":16.93},{"text":"All the things we say are forbidden by the constitution.","start":846.589,"stop":853.184,"duration":6.59},{"text":"But may I just point out that in the Eastern Railroad Conference case where it was contended the antitrust laws applied to a conspiracy involving dishonest act, unethical conduct on the part of the Railroad to elicit anti-trucking legislation.","start":853.184,"stop":878.178,"duration":24.99},{"text":"And there you said you would not assume that Congress intended to intrude upon this political area unless the act clearly so provides and this act doesn't clearly so provide.","start":878.178,"stop":892.635,"duration":14.46},{"text":"It says nothing about speech and debate.","start":892.635,"stop":896.162,"duration":3.53},{"text":"I say, you take this accordion upon which the government can play almost any tune on it under Chief Justice Taft's interpretation.","start":896.162,"stop":906.192,"duration":10.03},{"text":"But you've got to expound it and stretch it the way beyond that.","start":906.192,"stop":910.349,"duration":4.16},{"text":"Let's say that the Congress intended to bring the ethics of Congressman within its goals.","start":910.349,"stop":920.926,"duration":10.58}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Would your agreement go so far as to urge that Congress has no right to pass a law forbidding the taking of money for making a speech on the floor of Congress?","start":920.926,"stop":938.22,"duration":17.29}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm coming to that in a moment Your Honor but may I just conclude with this then I will deal with that.","start":938.22,"stop":944.605,"duration":6.38},{"text":"I say that Congress had no more intention to apply the statute to hire speech in the Congress and he did to authorize an imposition in hearsay, that's my first point.","start":944.605,"stop":961.326,"duration":16.72},{"text":"And if that's right then the decision of the Fourth Circuit which is unanimous should be affirmed that this was an invalid count.","start":961.326,"stop":975.587,"duration":14.26}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"That conclusion, you maybe right but would you mind illuminating that?","start":975.587,"stop":981.002,"duration":5.41}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, my first point is then that this conspiracy statute, Section 371 Mr. Johnson was charged of violating --- was charged of violating any bribery statute or any other statute conspiring for the United States by obstruction its government functions making a venal speech from the floor of the House.","start":981.002,"stop":1010.866,"duration":29.86},{"text":"We say that that Congress never intended that that 1867 statute should ever be applied to this matter, to this subject matter.","start":1010.866,"stop":1025.307,"duration":14.44},{"text":"That should entrench upon the right of freedom of legislative speech are effective.","start":1025.307,"stop":1033.127,"duration":7.82},{"text":"Now, may I point out what the government actually questioned in this case?","start":1033.127,"stop":1040.467,"duration":7.34},{"text":"What this evidence was?","start":1040.467,"stop":1043.076,"duration":2.61}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Before you get to that, I would like to know, I would like to know what is your position that Congress has no right to pass any law prohibiting a Congressman from taking money for making a speech on the floor of the Congress advocating anything--","start":1043.076,"stop":1067.412,"duration":24.34}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1067.412,"stop":1069.198,"duration":1.79}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"That's all I want to know from you.","start":1069.198,"stop":1071.107,"duration":1.91}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I'm sorry but that's very definitely my position.","start":1071.107,"stop":1074.602,"duration":3.5},{"text":"And that there is a major distinction between speech and utterance in the Congress and other official acts.","start":1074.602,"stop":1087.411,"duration":12.81},{"text":"Now, whether Congress can pass a valid bribery statute as applied to a vote I think is a very different subject -- it's not involved in this case but I think somewhat closer subject.","start":1087.411,"stop":1109.335,"duration":21.92},{"text":"And the reason that we have state the life of our country on freedom on speech that there can be no inquiry and to why speech is made.","start":1109.335,"stop":1134.089,"duration":24.75},{"text":"There can be no inquiry as to what purpose it serves.","start":1134.089,"stop":1139.426,"duration":5.34},{"text":"The reason is that even a venal speech, even a speech influenced by improper motives maybe the truth, maybe sound, maybe right that's why we can't --- would not stop coming those propaganda in this country just because its motivation maybe evil.","start":1139.426,"stop":1170.133,"duration":30.71}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"We've also just take their lives on honesty of public officials in the office, have we not?","start":1170.133,"stop":1178.737,"duration":8.6}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, there have been no widespread scandals of venal speeches in the Congress, no scholars ever advocated the great speech and debate clause should be limited and restricted, actually more crimes had been committed in the name of grudge.","start":1178.737,"stop":1206.046,"duration":27.31},{"text":"Two dangerous words in this case, and I think they're the most dangerous in our legal vocabulary.","start":1206.046,"stop":1213.458,"duration":7.41},{"text":"One is conspiracy and the other is bribe.","start":1213.458,"stop":1218.837,"duration":5.38},{"text":"Let me point out to you --","start":1218.837,"stop":1223.16,"duration":4.32}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm haven't yet been able to see how if we sustain a part from the other points.","start":1223.16,"stop":1228.612,"duration":5.45},{"text":"If we sustain this conviction how this would run against the spirit of the immunity from free debate?","start":1228.612,"stop":1236.698,"duration":8.09},{"text":"It's up on my head --","start":1236.698,"stop":1237.795,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm just coming to it.","start":1237.795,"stop":1239.227,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"You are always just coming to the --","start":1239.227,"stop":1240.426,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"I am here now --.","start":1240.426,"stop":1243.978,"duration":3.55},{"text":"Mr. Justice Douglas.","start":1243.978,"stop":1247.193,"duration":3.21},{"text":"The at a scene agreement that was charged in this indictment was an alleged agreement by Johnson to make a speech in the House, now, it didn't stop there.","start":1247.193,"stop":1263.278,"duration":16.09},{"text":"It was to make a speech in the House defending Maryland state savings and loans associations.","start":1263.278,"stop":1273.958,"duration":10.68},{"text":"Now, we say this charge required an inquiry into the content of the speech.","start":1273.958,"stop":1281.385,"duration":7.43},{"text":"Under that charge it was absolutely essential for the government to show that Mr. Johnson speech, what the speech on foreign policy, it wasn't a speech attacking the savings and loans associations.","start":1281.385,"stop":1295.27,"duration":13.88},{"text":"It was a speech supporting.","start":1295.27,"stop":1300.191,"duration":4.92},{"text":"Because if the substance of the speech had been of a different character its content would have denied the charge.","start":1300.191,"stop":1311.109,"duration":10.92},{"text":"In other words, the government in this case had to show content of the speech to establish the offense and so it put the speech in evidence and it didn't put it in to any restricted purpose or a limited purpose, it just put it in.","start":1311.109,"stop":1328.737,"duration":17.63}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Doub, you mentioned that there's no -- no scholars have ever advanced this idea, has it ever been seriously discussed in Stoller v. (Inaudible) prior to despair, rather the Congressman has the right to accept money to make the speech on the floor of the Congress.","start":1328.737,"stop":1358.067,"duration":29.33}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, the question is by what tribunal should it be punished by?","start":1358.067,"stop":1365.672,"duration":7.61}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I didn't ask you that --","start":1365.672,"stop":1366.795,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean, of course, he should be punished --","start":1366.795,"stop":1368.162,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"I didn't you ask you that, I asked you if the precise question that you present here has been seriously discussed in Stoller v. (Inaudible), because you haven't brought in your statement -- and ever advocated such a thing and I just wondered if that subject had been seriously discussed or ---","start":1368.162,"stop":1389.493,"duration":21.33}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, three law review articles have been published –- three law review articles have been published approving the Fourth Circuit decision.","start":1389.493,"stop":1398.441,"duration":8.95}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but I was thinking about before this thing –- this matter—","start":1398.441,"stop":1405.047,"duration":6.61}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think you've got –- no, I don't think so.","start":1405.047,"stop":1408.518,"duration":3.47},{"text":"I don't think so Mr. Chief Justice but you have to look to the great constitutional history involved here it's never been a question of whether a Congressman should be punished for any penal act, of course he should.","start":1408.518,"stop":1427.465,"duration":18.95},{"text":"In the case of speech and debate though our constitution reserves that area with discipline to each chamber of the Congress and each chamber can discipline and should.","start":1427.465,"stop":1444.499,"duration":17.03},{"text":"As a matter of fact you'll find the house of the Congress considered as an insult to the House for anyone to, for any member to accept a bribe for any official act he did.","start":1444.499,"stop":1457.433,"duration":12.93},{"text":"And even back in the 17th and 18th centuries there are numerable such cases where they acted on such charges against members.","start":1457.433,"stop":1471.838,"duration":14.4}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Doub, the other aspect of this case as I understand it is the petitioner was charged with accepting money and thereafter on account of the acceptance of the money, making representations to the attorney general and the Department of Justice.","start":1471.838,"stop":1495.269,"duration":23.43},{"text":"But now, I take it, you do not challenge the validity of that of that count.","start":1495.269,"stop":1501.691,"duration":6.42}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"No, those charges were -- the charge was the violation of a conflict of interest statute which forbid a member of Congress from accepting compensation for rendering services before an executive agency of the government.","start":1501.691,"stop":1520.403,"duration":18.71},{"text":"We never questioned that, the charge was right within the statute.","start":1520.403,"stop":1526.73,"duration":6.33},{"text":"The whole factual issue there was this, when Mr. Johnson after being told that this charge against Mr. Edlin and first colony was outrageous have been inspired by competitors was unjust and it was undisputed, he'd been told that.","start":1526.73,"stop":1554.55,"duration":27.82},{"text":"It was undisputed that he went to the – and saw the attorney general and told him that.","start":1554.55,"stop":1560.735,"duration":6.18},{"text":"It was undisputed also that he told him he didn't wish to interfere at all and all he was asking was to reveal the case on the merits.","start":1560.735,"stop":1570.966,"duration":10.23},{"text":"And he then had other meetings with the head of the criminal division on the same subject and Mr. Miller said yes, Mr. Johnson told him that.","start":1570.966,"stop":1578.673,"duration":7.71},{"text":"Now, the issue is --","start":1578.673,"stop":1581.678,"duration":3.01}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"However, that maybe I take it, you don't contend that he made a disclosure that he had accepted the money.","start":1581.678,"stop":1589.898,"duration":8.22}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I suggest Mr. Fortas, the whole issue was, was he paid for those services.","start":1589.898,"stop":1598.523,"duration":8.63},{"text":"It was our contention, he wasn't paid a cent, it was our contention that his legal fee -– the sums of money which he received in 1961 from March on were all legal fees from several land companies and from several savings and loan associations that he represented for legal work done.","start":1598.523,"stop":1624.242,"duration":25.72},{"text":"We didn't rest on merely his own testimony as to his legal services for them and Mr. Robinson but we brought in six lawyers, one from New York, one from Washington, one from Baltimore, one from southern Maryland but generally all of them to testify the certain aspects of his legal work.","start":1624.242,"stop":1644.231,"duration":19.99},{"text":"So the real issue under the substantive counts was, did those payment or those fees include payment for going to –- making those --","start":1644.231,"stop":1660,"duration":15.77}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I take it, you're pursuing that and I want to get your view as to what might conceivably be the important issue here, I take it but your position is that corresponds with that with the Court of Appeals, the Fourth Circuit that is to say that the count and evidence relating to the speech and so infects the conviction, that it cannot stand even though you don't challenge the indictment on the basis of taking money for purposes of inducing the Congressman to make a representation to the Department Justice.","start":1660,"stop":1704.956,"duration":44.96},{"text":"Is that your position?","start":1704.956,"stop":1706.389,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Our position here is that this unlawful first count and the evidence submitted under it violated and did infect the jury's verdict under the substantive counts, it was hardly contested whether he was paid for his trips to the department and we say that no one could say with assurance that the jury was not prejudiced by the unlawful charges as to the speech in the conspiracy count.","start":1706.389,"stop":1739.512,"duration":33.12},{"text":"As a matter of fact, although the government reserved that issue, they never contested it in their brief here.","start":1739.512,"stop":1750.323,"duration":10.81},{"text":"May I say this about this or about the evidence?","start":1750.323,"stop":1756.679,"duration":6.36},{"text":"The alleged bribe of $500.00 to make a speech after Johnson had been defeated for reelection three weeks after the indictment by the republican opponent.","start":1756.679,"stop":1774.879,"duration":18.2},{"text":"But when he got to trial, the $500.00 bribe became a political campaign gift.","start":1774.879,"stop":1785.108,"duration":10.23},{"text":"It wasn't paid under the table.","start":1785.108,"stop":1787.229,"duration":2.12},{"text":"It wasn't paid in cash.","start":1787.229,"stop":1789.259,"duration":2.03},{"text":"It was paid by check with a covering letter and it was endorsed by Johnson over to his treasurer and he deposited it in his bank account with other contributions and he reported it to the Circuit Court along with all other contributions, so it was received, recorded, used and reported as in the case of other contributions and it was used to help elect John F. Kennedy and Lyndon Johnson and Congressman Johnson, like all the others.","start":1789.259,"stop":1825.716,"duration":36.46},{"text":"I'm not going to go to into the evidence about this speech, except to say there wasn't any evidence that Johnson ever agreed to make a speech for that small campaign contribution.","start":1825.716,"stop":1838.373,"duration":12.66},{"text":"There wasn't any -– and I don't believe when you look at this record you can say that he did.","start":1838.373,"stop":1846.222,"duration":7.85},{"text":"But we contend -–","start":1846.222,"stop":1847.692,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Was that the only money he received, $500.00?","start":1847.692,"stop":1850.58,"duration":2.89}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"That was the only money he received anywhere around this time of this speech.","start":1850.58,"stop":1856.21,"duration":5.63},{"text":"Now the –-","start":1856.21,"stop":1856.333,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"How much or told did they prove he took?","start":1856.333,"stop":1860.687,"duration":4.35}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, the government never even contended he received any money except this $500.00 for the speech.","start":1860.687,"stop":1869.739,"duration":9.05},{"text":"There were two checks paid to his office that he endorsed over to the public printer for the ordering reprints of the speech within the next 30 days.","start":1869.739,"stop":1882.707,"duration":12.97},{"text":"Then there was a retainer paid to him in the fall, I think it was about September 1st, of $1,000.00 when he was engaged to represent, act as local council for Robinson, who is general council of a mortgage company in Florida and to savings and loan associations.","start":1882.707,"stop":1907.765,"duration":25.06},{"text":"That was all for 1960.","start":1907.765,"stop":1910.724,"duration":2.96},{"text":"The speech is made in June 16.","start":1910.724,"stop":1913.464,"duration":2.74},{"text":"Now in ‘61, he received -– he did a lot of legal, he received a lot of checks -– as a matter of fact, I would say they totaled, I think about $19,000.00.","start":1913.464,"stop":1926.12,"duration":12.66},{"text":"Out of those checks he paid local council in Virginia and in southern Maryland about $6,000.00, a local council in Baltimore $1,000.","start":1926.12,"stop":1938.532,"duration":12.41},{"text":"He had the responsibility of foreclosing a 15 million-dollar mortgage.","start":1938.532,"stop":1942.762,"duration":4.23},{"text":"But the speech itself was related to a subject of major interest to the state of Maryland.","start":1942.762,"stop":1960.775,"duration":18.01},{"text":"It didn't relate to an Idaho power dam that Mr. Johnson couldn't have any possible interest in.","start":1960.775,"stop":1968.582,"duration":7.81},{"text":"You will find it's an able speech, an intelligent speech and it's a good speech and it was one that any Maryland Congressman would logically make after the –- in his paper article calling all Maryland savings and loan associations (Inaudible).","start":1968.582,"stop":2001.558,"duration":32.98},{"text":"I think, the essential issue here, the court please is whether the speech and debate clause prohibits an inquiry only into what it said in the Congress as the government contends.","start":2001.558,"stop":2017.796,"duration":16.24},{"text":"But whether it prohibits an inquiry into why it was said.","start":2017.796,"stop":2023.805,"duration":6.01},{"text":"As we contend and the Fourth Circuit held and we say that the making of any speech involves a speech process and that certainly includes its purpose of thinking behind it, its preparation, its motivation, source material, and its use.","start":2023.805,"stop":2050.027,"duration":26.22},{"text":"All should be within the clause and this nearly raised the antecedent agreement to make a speech.","start":2050.027,"stop":2061.183,"duration":11.16},{"text":"We say that's an integral part of the speech process and we say to deny this is just to emasculate and destroy the constitution.","start":2061.183,"stop":2074.321,"duration":13.14}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You haven't quite got into the question I asked you some time ago.","start":2074.321,"stop":2079.638,"duration":5.32},{"text":"Do you contend that if the he just took money for making a speech that the Congress could not prohibit that?","start":2079.638,"stop":2091.621,"duration":11.98}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"The congress could act on it itself in discipline and then –-","start":2091.621,"stop":2097.081,"duration":5.46}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Couldn't make a crime for --","start":2097.081,"stop":2099.701,"duration":2.62}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":2099.701,"stop":2101.6,"duration":1.9},{"text":"I don't this is consistent with the great dramatic legislative history of the speech and debate clause prohibiting anyone from questioning speech and debate and then its -– Your Honor, you've already said and told us that claim of unworthy purpose would not destroy the privilege.","start":2101.6,"stop":2133.667,"duration":32.07},{"text":"You've even said dishonest official act.","start":2133.667,"stop":2141.908,"duration":8.24},{"text":"So that's what you said intending --","start":2141.908,"stop":2144.159,"duration":2.25}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, suppose we had a very simple statement of facts here and if we're not to contest it and all the facts that we had were that Congressman A had agreed with certain interest that when he would make a speech on the floor of the Congress, for thousands of dollars and he was paid that money for that purpose and he was arrested thereafter -- before let's say his speech was made.","start":2144.159,"stop":2190.125,"duration":45.97},{"text":"Would the Congress have the authority to proscribe such conduct?","start":2190.125,"stop":2197.303,"duration":7.18}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"I say no, I say no.","start":2197.303,"stop":2201.019,"duration":3.72},{"text":"I say that would be in the same category as if a Congressman was charged with not speaking, being paid not to speak against a bill or for a bill and being silent, silence was just as eloquent with the speech.","start":2201.019,"stop":2221.425,"duration":20.41},{"text":"So I say both categories, you'd be questioning a motivation of speech –","start":2221.425,"stop":2226.954,"duration":5.53}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose that this was a tax case and he was being sued because he didn't report this.","start":2226.954,"stop":2232.057,"duration":5.1},{"text":"Suppose he was charged of having received $10,000.00 or whatever it was in that speech in the Congress and the Internal Revenue sues him, that would be inquiring about your theory into the speech I suppose –-","start":2232.057,"stop":2246.876,"duration":14.82}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I wouldn't.","start":2246.876,"stop":2250.277,"duration":3.4},{"text":"That would be the receipt of income –-","start":2250.277,"stop":2251.999,"duration":1.72}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Beg your pardon.","start":2251.999,"stop":2252.916,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"That would be the receipt of income --","start":2252.916,"stop":2254.144,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what this case is about, receipt of income.","start":2254.144,"stop":2260.015,"duration":5.87}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think there's a difference there.","start":2260.015,"stop":2263.865,"duration":3.85},{"text":"I think –-","start":2263.865,"stop":2264.807,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if there is a difference, I just wonder whether it is a material difference.","start":2264.807,"stop":2268.773,"duration":3.97}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, of course it's a hypothetical question case.","start":2268.773,"stop":2272.586,"duration":3.81},{"text":"What you present and the Chief Justice presents are very different from the case, we have here.","start":2272.586,"stop":2279.207,"duration":6.62},{"text":"I'm just speculating about it.","start":2279.207,"stop":2280.672,"duration":1.47},{"text":"I would say that in the case of –-","start":2280.672,"stop":2282.301,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, considered that they have to introduce the speech, they have to show that the speech that was made and the funds that were paid and the speech therefore would be in the record just like in your case and therefore the speech would be an under-challenge and inquiry by your standard?","start":2282.301,"stop":2297.838,"duration":15.54}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if that occurred then it would still be in my position.","start":2297.838,"stop":2300.809,"duration":2.97},{"text":"It couldn't be done.","start":2300.809,"stop":2302.175,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"So whatever the tax immunity case --","start":2302.175,"stop":2307.409,"duration":5.23}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Actually, in the case, Chief Justice- – it's hard to conceive and visualize the case you mentioned.","start":2307.409,"stop":2315.762,"duration":8.35},{"text":"As a matter of fact, 300 years there's never been such a charge as this.","start":2315.762,"stop":2320.355,"duration":4.59}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What do you find if anything in the early in this case on this question?","start":2320.355,"stop":2330.136,"duration":9.78}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Harlan, the history and it's the most dramatic history of any constitutional provision we have and the best documented and the most colorful.","start":2330.136,"stop":2342.785,"duration":12.65},{"text":"It shows there was no distinction between content and motivation.","start":2342.785,"stop":2347.946,"duration":5.16},{"text":"It shows that this new found effort of the government to say that there's a –- that the constitutional provision was only designed to protect the substance, the content of speech.","start":2347.946,"stop":2361.552,"duration":13.61},{"text":"We say that that's denied by the history because the most famous case in England didn't even relate to content.","start":2361.552,"stop":2369.469,"duration":7.92}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Are there any in these cases that view bribery of members of the Parliament?","start":2369.469,"stop":2375.738,"duration":6.27}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Never by the judiciary.","start":2375.738,"stop":2378.107,"duration":2.37},{"text":"There are plenty of cases and –-","start":2378.107,"stop":2379.388,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I'm talking about the judiciaries.","start":2379.388,"stop":2380.998,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":2380.998,"stop":2382.102,"duration":1.1},{"text":"The crowd has never brought such a charge.","start":2382.102,"stop":2385.751,"duration":3.65},{"text":"And we have pulled together more comprehensively and we think for the first time in whole history of this and we believe you'll find that everything that Peter Wentworth said and Elliot said and other great parliamentarians and everything we say that the House of Commons said in its (Inaudible) deny this distinction between content and purpose.","start":2385.751,"stop":2420.904,"duration":35.15},{"text":"The most significant case is a case form the 16th century, where the crown charged a member of commons, with introducing a bill to regulate the tin industry and he was charged with having a financial interest in the bill.","start":2420.904,"stop":2441.561,"duration":20.66},{"text":"The content wasn't involved.","start":2441.561,"stop":2443.252,"duration":1.69},{"text":"He was convicted.","start":2443.252,"stop":2445.607,"duration":2.36},{"text":"The House of Commons attempted to annul that conviction indeed and they also at the same time said that they were -– these charges were invalid.","start":2445.607,"stop":2458.673,"duration":13.07},{"text":"The judges -- and from that time on, the parliamentarians contended that this (Inaudible) Act was a general act applicable to all members of congress, all members of the House of Commons and applicable to -- and denying the crown any authority to make any charge of any kind whether inquiring into their acts in their chamber.","start":2458.673,"stop":2486.116,"duration":27.44}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Would your argument lead us to the conclusion that Congress has no right to make bribery of a Congressman, a crime?","start":2486.116,"stop":2500.392,"duration":14.28}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Outside of the field of speech and debate, and I'm clear as to that that they can't do that.","start":2500.392,"stop":2509.667,"duration":9.28},{"text":"But outside of that, when you deal with official acts other than that, I think when that case is presented to you, which it isn't here today, the issue will be, could Congress delegate or consent or wave the privilege?","start":2509.667,"stop":2534.888,"duration":25.22},{"text":"And did it do so by the enactment of such a statute?","start":2534.888,"stop":2541.447,"duration":6.56},{"text":"That would be the real issue.","start":2541.447,"stop":2543.276,"duration":1.83},{"text":"Now, ordinarily when the constitution has conferred the power upon the Congress, Congress may delegate that power to the executive or even to the state, as in the case of the commerce power.","start":2543.276,"stop":2558.547,"duration":15.27},{"text":"But you have a more difficult problem here because the speech and debate clause is not cast in terms of granting a power to Congress.","start":2558.547,"stop":2574.607,"duration":16.06},{"text":"It says speech and debate shall not be questioned elsewhere.","start":2574.607,"stop":2579.973,"duration":5.37},{"text":"So it's a denial, prohibition of power in the executives and the judiciary.","start":2579.973,"stop":2588.31,"duration":8.34},{"text":"So when you – if and when you reach that question, that will be a great question.","start":2588.31,"stop":2595.756,"duration":7.45}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"What would your argument leave us to conclude, do you think?","start":2595.756,"stop":2602.998,"duration":7.24}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"This charge is absolutely violating from the speech and debate clause, this conspiracy charge.","start":2602.998,"stop":2613.044,"duration":10.05},{"text":"It resulted as elaborate into Mr. Johnson's mental processes, was he influenced by the campaign contribution or not.","start":2613.044,"stop":2629.118,"duration":16.07},{"text":"Why in the Fourth Circuit the government's brief said, surely the government did not have to prove that Johnson's soul motive –- that Johnson's soul motive was the campaign contribution or to aid Edler (ph) and Robinson.","start":2629.118,"stop":2659.173,"duration":30.05},{"text":"I thought in the outset that this violated the clause and I think so still.","start":2659.173,"stop":2666.918,"duration":7.75},{"text":"As a matter of fact, the publication, the allegations that he ordered reprints of his speech and was interested in their distribution.","start":2666.918,"stop":2677.948,"duration":11.03},{"text":"That was a violation of the speech and debate clause.","start":2677.948,"stop":2684.559,"duration":6.61},{"text":"You remember it wrongly, Mr. Justice Douglas and Mr. Justice Black.","start":2684.559,"stop":2691.624,"duration":7.06},{"text":"The other judges didn't reach the point to held that there could be no inquiry in the distribution of books.","start":2691.624,"stop":2703.822,"duration":12.2}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose we wanted to include that the time in this case we spoke out that the Congress could pass an act making bribery a crime and suppose the Congressman was arrested for accepting a bribe and it developed in addition from voting, and developed that in addition to voting he had made a speech urging other Congressmen to vote as he did.","start":2703.822,"stop":2740.789,"duration":36.97},{"text":"Would that immunize him?","start":2740.789,"stop":2748.602,"duration":7.81}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not sure, I followed you but I think I would Your Honor –","start":2748.602,"stop":2751.895,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"It's a very simple thing.","start":2751.895,"stop":2754.577,"duration":2.68},{"text":"If Congressman A takes that bribe form Mr. B to vote for and urge, passage of a bill.","start":2754.577,"stop":2768.233,"duration":13.66},{"text":"He accepts the money for it.","start":2768.233,"stop":2771.135,"duration":2.9},{"text":"Then in pursuance of that, he not only votes for the bill, but he makes a speech on the floor of the Congress urging other Congressmen to vote for it as a part of the bribe.","start":2771.135,"stop":2787.806,"duration":16.67},{"text":"Would that – the fact that he made the speech immunize against the charge of bribery?","start":2787.806,"stop":2796.215,"duration":8.41}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it certainly -– I don't think the court and the executive could go into that speech.","start":2796.215,"stop":2805.5,"duration":9.28},{"text":"Assuming that you hereafter hold in a case when the question comes before you, that the Congress can enact an anti-bribery statute applicable to official acts, other than speech and debate and assuming there's a prosecution under that, I would still say the government could put an evidence of speech he made, even though it was related to it.","start":2805.5,"stop":2836.862,"duration":31.36},{"text":"May I point this out?","start":2836.862,"stop":2838.228,"duration":1.37},{"text":"Members of Congress, the elected representatives of the people, they necessarily accept and rely on in their political campaigns, upon campaign contributions.","start":2838.228,"stop":2853.116,"duration":14.89},{"text":"In the case of a member of Congress, he represents the farm interests, his contributions will come from the farm organizations.","start":2853.116,"stop":2863.189,"duration":10.07},{"text":"If he is a chap in civil rights, his contributions will probably come from associations interested in civil rights.","start":2863.189,"stop":2873.086,"duration":9.9},{"text":"If he is a champion of labor, they will come from the labor unions.","start":2873.086,"stop":2878.536,"duration":5.45},{"text":"Now, the power of the executive was such that a member of Congress in his legislative utterances, favoring or deemed the favor of special interest groups to contribute to his political campaigns.","start":2878.536,"stop":2900.967,"duration":22.43},{"text":"But he was influenced by those campaign contributions or he may not have seen an agreement with his contributors to make a speech in the Congress.","start":2900.967,"stop":2912.474,"duration":11.51},{"text":"I say that would be highly dangerous.","start":2912.474,"stop":2915.062,"duration":2.59}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, must we assume that this money came to Congressman Johnson as a campaign contribution?","start":2915.062,"stop":2922.97,"duration":7.91},{"text":"I assume that you –-","start":2922.97,"stop":2923.873,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"No question about that –-","start":2923.873,"stop":2924.709,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sure the jury didn't believe that.","start":2924.709,"stop":2928.162,"duration":3.45}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"With all the covering letters said it was -- it wasn't -– it didn't come under the table, it wasn't in cash, it was openly made.","start":2928.162,"stop":2939.833,"duration":11.67},{"text":"Johnson didn't get cent of it.","start":2939.833,"stop":2941.631,"duration":1.8},{"text":"Personally, he endorsed it over to his treasurer and it was deposited – treated just as all the other contributions were to his campaign –- but coming back to this, I say this charge alone that someone spoke in favor of the interest of someone who had contributed to -- who had been a contributor in his campaign.","start":2941.631,"stop":2971.799,"duration":30.17},{"text":"A charge could be politically destructive as it was with Johnson.","start":2971.799,"stop":2978.452,"duration":6.65},{"text":"In spite of his presumption of innocence, he was defeated.","start":2978.452,"stop":2983.51,"duration":5.06},{"text":"At the trial, a speech is conceded; a political campaign is conceded, so then, it's necessary for the member of Congress in his defense to explain his mental processes, his bona fide purposes, his inner most thoughts, and to demonstrate that he would have said the same thing regardless of the campaign contribution.","start":2983.51,"stop":3012.222,"duration":28.71},{"text":"And, I say --","start":3012.222,"stop":3013.149,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And, a voting bribery case, should it make any difference if a man would have voted the way he did, if he hadn't accepted the bribe?","start":3013.149,"stop":3025.458,"duration":12.31}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think so.","start":3025.458,"stop":3026.743,"duration":1.28},{"text":"I don't think so","start":3026.743,"stop":3027.979,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But wouldn't the same -- so far as that principle is involved, would it be the same thing so far as the speech is concerned.","start":3027.979,"stop":3034.854,"duration":6.88},{"text":"No, because speech has a more fundamental purpose in the life of that country.","start":3034.854,"stop":3041.346,"duration":6.49},{"text":"Speech would be restrained, it will be curtailed, and it would be inhibited for this reason, Mr. Chief Justice, no one would dare make a speech that could be interpreted as favoring the interest of a contributor.","start":3041.346,"stop":3058.939,"duration":17.59},{"text":"You could speak against his interest safely and freely, but how could you dare say, “Defend the position of your contributors, ” that's where you retrain and curtail freedom of speech.","start":3058.939,"stop":3079.947,"duration":21.01}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But making contributions isn't the crime here, this charge.","start":3079.947,"stop":3088.875,"duration":8.93}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but that's --","start":3088.875,"stop":3089.46,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Crime here is --","start":3089.46,"stop":3090.435,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what the evidence showed it was --","start":3090.435,"stop":3092.175,"duration":1.74}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's' something else but I mean in written -- we're talking here about is presumably about a case where the money goes into the Congressman and the Senator's pocket, aren't we?","start":3092.175,"stop":3108.965,"duration":16.79}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, yes.","start":3108.965,"stop":3111.22,"duration":2.25}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"He makes a crime and then they charge --","start":3111.22,"stop":3115.291,"duration":4.07}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that was -- yes, so we have motions for --","start":3115.291,"stop":3124.983,"duration":9.69}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Jury trial.","start":3124.983,"stop":3139.26,"duration":14.28}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"I'd say again that there is this distinction between voting and other official acts and speech.","start":3139.26,"stop":3150.942,"duration":11.68},{"text":"I'd say, we have staked the life of this nation on the capacity of free speech to develop truth and to enable truth to gain acceptance in the marketplace of ideas.","start":3150.942,"stop":3165.882,"duration":14.94},{"text":"And if that's true for the ordinary citizen, surely it might -- cannot possibly be less true for members of Congress, and whatever your ruling maybe in some future case on a venal vote in the Congress that issue is presented which it is not here, we submit that the basic uninhibited, free speech principles mean that it cannot be curtailed because of a charge that it was hired or influenced by a political campaign contribution or any other unethical consideration.","start":3165.882,"stop":3206.2,"duration":40.32}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you suggesting that if you did not have a free speech, would they –","start":3206.2,"stop":3216.487,"duration":10.29}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"I have serious doubt, whether onto the First Amendment, a criminal charge could ever be made against the editor of a newspaper or any other publisher that involved in inquiry into his motives and whether they were honest or not in anything but that that publisher said.","start":3216.487,"stop":3241.746,"duration":25.26}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Congress –-","start":3241.746,"stop":3243.733,"duration":1.99}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I don't think we need to go there.","start":3243.733,"stop":3245.978,"duration":2.24},{"text":"I think it could be -- I think it could be, Mr. Justice Harlan, but where you have on the one hand a general First Amendment right and on the other you have a specific, unqualified category clause in the Constitution dealing with speech and debate in the Congress, it seems to me that the Court would naturally look to the -- and interpret the specific provision rather than the general one.","start":3245.978,"stop":3283.345,"duration":37.37},{"text":"But even a hired speech, even a speech influenced by a campaign contribution or desire to aid private interest, the speech maybe right, it maybe convincing, and it maybe conducive to truth on its merits.","start":3283.345,"stop":3305.273,"duration":21.93},{"text":"It maybe true and that's why you can't permit any inquiry into it.","start":3305.273,"stop":3318.614,"duration":13.34},{"text":"If I have any time left, would Mr. Chief Justice, you permit my -- Professor Louisell to use us that time?","start":3318.614,"stop":3329.315,"duration":10.7},{"text":"I'd be very grateful.","start":3329.315,"stop":3330.365,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I will Mr. Doub, and you may have an extra five minutes if you wish, Professor, I would give extra five minutes to Mr. Rosenberg, you may –-","start":3330.365,"stop":3347.275,"duration":16.91}]},{"speakerName":"David W. Louisell","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":3347.275,"stop":3349.923,"duration":2.65},{"text":"One of the things that has mystified me since the argument here on Wednesday is how, by the use of words, the impression can be conveyed to whatever the verbal formula that this prosecution didn't involve a penetrating inquiry into everything we need, when we talk about speech.","start":3349.923,"stop":3380.774,"duration":30.85},{"text":"The psychological, the moral, the human characteristics that go into making a speech, the involving as it does, the research, the preparation, the thinking, the balancing of interest, will I talk or won't I talk and all that sort of thing culminating finally in the speech.","start":3380.774,"stop":3400.805,"duration":20.03},{"text":"This Court, which has never been fooled at least in recent years by a mere terminology or evidence, as you pointed out in the New York Times case, we penetrate to the realities and we're not satisfied by state characterization as a libel or treason or sudden some such thing.","start":3400.805,"stop":3418.752,"duration":17.95}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Louisell, don't we have the same realities insofar as the voting is concerned?","start":3418.752,"stop":3424.851,"duration":6.1}]},{"speakerName":"David W. Louisell","textObjs":[{"text":"When it comes to voting, Your Honor, note how specifically, first of all, the words of the Constitution are –-","start":3424.851,"stop":3432.614,"duration":7.76}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"No, so far as --","start":3432.614,"stop":3433.049,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"David W. Louisell","textObjs":[{"text":"For any speech or debate --","start":3433.049,"stop":3434.783,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"So far as realities are concerned and research and the voting independently and all of those things that you mentioned are concerned, do we not have those same realities and possibly more so in voting and we do in --","start":3434.783,"stop":3449.468,"duration":14.68}]},{"speakerName":"David W. Louisell","textObjs":[{"text":"To a degree, Your Honor, exactly states the situation.","start":3449.468,"stop":3453.2,"duration":3.73},{"text":"Many of the same type of considerations are pertinent.","start":3453.2,"stop":3456.164,"duration":2.96},{"text":"But notice the difference.","start":3456.164,"stop":3457.923,"duration":1.76},{"text":"Notice that the function of speech, Your Honor, is to influence, to urge, to advocate, and notice that a speech may do that and they do so properly.","start":3457.923,"stop":3470.136,"duration":12.21},{"text":"And, I think the reading of the text of this speech in the appendix will show you what an appeal, it was to common sense and judgment.","start":3470.136,"stop":3478.226,"duration":8.09},{"text":"A speech is aimed at convincing and that is why the Constitution draws such a sharp dichotomy.","start":3478.226,"stop":3486.65,"duration":8.42},{"text":"That is why the Constitution is willing to create an absolute barrier for any speech or debate, he shall not be held responsible in any other place and notice --","start":3486.65,"stop":3500.519,"duration":13.87}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"I have an idea.","start":3500.519,"stop":3501.31,"duration":0.79},{"text":"Most people would rather have a vote on the speech though wouldn't they?","start":3501.31,"stop":3504.529,"duration":3.22}]},{"speakerName":"David W. Louisell","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but most people may prefer, Your Honor, it doesn't seem to go the heart of the matter because it gives to speech and debate, that the English tradition of 400, 500 years has been devoted.","start":3504.529,"stop":3517.427,"duration":12.9},{"text":"It is to the absolute guarantee of speech and debate that our constitution is so absolutely committed.","start":3517.427,"stop":3525.473,"duration":8.05},{"text":"Now, Your Honor, I asked the question, would the bribery statute necessarily call by a condemnation of what the government attempted to do here?","start":3525.473,"stop":3536.099,"duration":10.63},{"text":"Then although it's already been aptly pointed out that the bribery statute isn't involved here, it is the penetrating question that forces an analysis and that is why, I maintain, it so important to study the history of the speech and debate, to the English years and to the Civil War period and into our Constitution.","start":3536.099,"stop":3556.284,"duration":20.18},{"text":"And I maintain, it's very important to realize, particularly on congressional intent, Congress has never tried to reach a prohibition for judicial purposes that is for prosecution purposes.","start":3556.284,"stop":3570.715,"duration":14.43},{"text":"On speech or debate, it's never made the attempt.","start":3570.715,"stop":3573.981,"duration":3.27},{"text":"It has made the attempt to prohibit the bribery of a vote.","start":3573.981,"stop":3578.844,"duration":4.86},{"text":"It has made that attempt and incidentally, I can find no instance in American history where there has even been a prosecution for the vote.","start":3578.844,"stop":3587.955,"duration":9.11},{"text":"That alone for speech and debate, I had wanted to mention to the Court --","start":3587.955,"stop":3594.393,"duration":6.44}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Does that mean there shouldn't have been?","start":3594.393,"stop":3596.423,"duration":2.03}]},{"speakerName":"David W. Louisell","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon.","start":3596.423,"stop":3596.922,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Does that there shouldn't have been?","start":3596.922,"stop":3597.973,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"David W. Louisell","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it doesn't mean there shouldn't have been, Your Honor, but what it means to me is this, that through most of -- to all of American history up to this prosecution, the executive and the judiciary have been willing to abide the constitutional judgment, that the inappropriate place to penalize this sort of conduct that is alleged in this case is in the Chamber, and we all know how effective a disciplinary action by a Chamber of Congress can be in curtailing improprieties.","start":3597.973,"stop":3631.852,"duration":33.88},{"text":"That's the judgment of the Constitution and if it's read against the background of the English history, I don't see how there can be any other judgment than that of the Fourth Circuit reached.","start":3631.852,"stop":3643.082,"duration":11.23}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Does your argument carry you far enough to say that Congress has no power then to proscribe as a criminal act bribery of a Congressman?","start":3643.082,"stop":3656.054,"duration":12.97}]},{"speakerName":"David W. Louisell","textObjs":[{"text":"It is not necessary to reach that conclusion, to uphold the Fourth Circuit.","start":3656.054,"stop":3659.581,"duration":3.53},{"text":"By no means, it is perfectly possible.","start":3659.581,"stop":3662.829,"duration":3.25}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But, is it necessary to –- if we follow your argument to its logical conclusion?","start":3662.829,"stop":3670.402,"duration":7.57}]},{"speakerName":"David W. Louisell","textObjs":[{"text":"If you follow the argument to its logical conclusion, and it maybe an excellent illustration that a page of history is worth a volume of logic.","start":3670.402,"stop":3679.795,"duration":9.39}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Then let's have a little logic for a moment.","start":3679.795,"stop":3681.66,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"David W. Louisell","textObjs":[{"text":"Even if you follow to its logical conclusion, Your Honor, and a perfectly driving type of penetrating inquiry to make, I'd still say no.","start":3681.66,"stop":3693.546,"duration":11.89},{"text":"I'd still say it's possible for Congress to condemn the bribery of a vote, but absolutely -- by means of a judicial prosecution, but it's absolutely impossible to make an inquiry into the motive of speech that is tuned over to the executive and the judiciary.","start":3693.546,"stop":3711.624,"duration":18.08},{"text":"If, Your Honor, is that maybe, perhaps, the defect of the brief --","start":3711.624,"stop":3715.66,"duration":4.04}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that would be true if -- our question is what is the motive?","start":3715.66,"stop":3719.061,"duration":3.4},{"text":"But, the question here is did he get a $1,000.00?","start":3719.061,"stop":3723.206,"duration":4.14}]},{"speakerName":"David W. Louisell","textObjs":[{"text":"But this is just burying the question of motive and basis for the speech, Mr. Justice Douglas, under the mere phraseology, if the Government comes up for the first time in this Court with have seen incumbent.","start":3723.206,"stop":3736.6,"duration":13.39}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"You bury it by saying this isn't the realm of motive?","start":3736.6,"stop":3740.2,"duration":3.6}]},{"speakerName":"David W. Louisell","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I don't think it's burying to inquire, what are the psychological realities of the speech-making process?","start":3740.2,"stop":3746.914,"duration":6.71},{"text":"And to me, it came that you can have a prosecution of this kind in respect of everything other than the mere delivery of the speech is highly artificial to me.","start":3746.914,"stop":3759.87,"duration":12.96},{"text":"Not always --","start":3759.87,"stop":3760.827,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Nobody's saying that.","start":3760.827,"stop":3761.79,"duration":0.96},{"text":"All they're saying is can you -- can you prove the he got a thousand or ten thousand or what not for making a speech?","start":3761.79,"stop":3768.71,"duration":6.92}]},{"speakerName":"David W. Louisell","textObjs":[{"text":"But the proof of the effect of anything prior to the speech, the $5, 000 or the $10,000.00 when it's an integral part, how do you prove that the speech was the consequence of it?","start":3768.71,"stop":3782.268,"duration":13.56}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you would agree with Mr. Doub then, that this was an income tax case.","start":3782.268,"stop":3785.372,"duration":3.1},{"text":"You couldn't –- to get a deficiency assessment because you get --","start":3785.372,"stop":3788.307,"duration":2.93}]},{"speakerName":"David W. Louisell","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, that has to be very precisely analyzed to course of a --","start":3788.307,"stop":3791.372,"duration":3.07}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"This has to be precisely analyzed.","start":3791.372,"stop":3793.519,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"David W. Louisell","textObjs":[{"text":"If a Congressman gets $10,000.00, he's obliged to report that as income -- if it's income.","start":3793.519,"stop":3799.676,"duration":6.16},{"text":"Of course, he's obliged to report it.","start":3799.676,"stop":3802.612,"duration":2.94},{"text":"Could he be prosecuted for receiving?","start":3802.612,"stop":3807.615,"duration":5},{"text":"Can he escape the fact that it's income?","start":3807.615,"stop":3809.585,"duration":1.97},{"text":"There's no problem there.","start":3809.585,"stop":3810.835,"duration":1.25},{"text":"He's got to report the income.","start":3810.835,"stop":3812.766,"duration":1.93},{"text":"If he's prosecuted for evading it --","start":3812.766,"stop":3814.819,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that sure would slow down in making speeches for money.","start":3814.819,"stop":3817.857,"duration":3.04}]},{"speakerName":"David W. Louisell","textObjs":[{"text":"If he's prosecuted for evading it, Your Honor, there's no inhibition of the Speech and Debate Clause except that the use of the contents of a speech, the use of the speech itself could not be an item of evidence under the Speech and Debate Clause.","start":3817.857,"stop":3834.365,"duration":16.51},{"text":"If Your Honors will carefully note how many instances the Government depended on the contents of the speech, and I sat here in amazement, when I heard innuendo to the contrary during the prosecution of this case, as we point out first of all on page 28 of the brief, note the words of the Fourth Circuit.","start":3834.365,"stop":3855.564,"duration":21.2},{"text":"After their careful analysis, the speech was more than an incidental feature of the conspiracy charge.","start":3855.564,"stop":3862.313,"duration":6.75},{"text":"Only one half of the testimony introduced at the trial related to the speech.","start":3862.313,"stop":3867.209,"duration":4.9},{"text":"Notice what we point out about the nature of the indictment.","start":3867.209,"stop":3870.159,"duration":2.95},{"text":"By quoting from the indictment, on pages 29 and 30, how many of the overt acts were directly tied up with the speech making process, the delivery of the speech.","start":3870.159,"stop":3882.392,"duration":12.23},{"text":"Notice that the fourth overt act in this indictment that we set forth on page 47 and 48.","start":3882.392,"stop":3890.101,"duration":7.71},{"text":"The very thing the Government relied upon, Your Honor, the fourth overt act that on or about June 30th, 1960 in the District of Columbia, the defendant Johnson delivered a speech on the floor of the House of Representatives.","start":3890.101,"stop":3904.572,"duration":14.47},{"text":"Notice what the trial judge charged as we set forth on page 68 of the brief that, “two separate conspiracies”.","start":3904.572,"stop":3914.59,"duration":10.02},{"text":"The first, beginning on April 1, 1960, to defraud the United States of its governmental functions largely by the making of the speech by defendant Johnson and distributions of reprints thereof.","start":3914.59,"stop":3927.312,"duration":12.72},{"text":"How much more connection can you have between the facts which a normal human psychology precede the making of the speech and the contents of the speech itself.","start":3927.312,"stop":3939.959,"duration":12.65},{"text":"I think it's almost demonstrable to an almost a certainty that the very contents of the speech, where the heart of this prosecution, and notice in the most famous case in this connection that Your Honors can read, the Strode case, it didn't involve the contents of the speech at all.","start":3939.959,"stop":3960.119,"duration":20.16},{"text":"It involved the alleged corrupt interest of a member of parliament in having a private interest in the bill that he introduced in parliament.","start":3960.119,"stop":3968.114,"duration":7.99},{"text":"Then after generations of struggle in England, the Act that condemned the interference of the judiciary with parliamentary freedom there was made a permanent part of English constitutional history.","start":3968.114,"stop":3980.955,"duration":12.84},{"text":"Let's not -- this Court has with penetrating realization of a necessity of protecting constitutional grants.","start":3980.955,"stop":3990.267,"duration":9.31},{"text":"This Court has gone to the realities over and over again in the free speech area against the most emotional charges, against the claims of libel and slander and even of treason.","start":3990.267,"stop":4002.839,"duration":12.57},{"text":"We penetrate to the realities.","start":4002.839,"stop":4004.584,"duration":1.74},{"text":"Let's not feel that's the word bribery, even though it can be uttered with the most base innuendoes.","start":4004.584,"stop":4012.975,"duration":8.39},{"text":"Let us not permit that to hide the realities from us in this case.","start":4012.975,"stop":4018.169,"duration":5.19},{"text":"Let's remember we have a constitutional provision here that is as specific, as definite, as well founded in English tradition as any words that you can pick out of the Constitution.","start":4018.169,"stop":4033.156,"duration":14.99},{"text":"And, lastly, let us never forget that there is something terribly sacred, significant, and basic in all provisions about speech, that it can be distinguished, that Congress has distinguished it by its own willingness to limit its condemnation to the three words of action, vote or decision but never has indicated any waiver, any desire or willingness to waive what the Constitution makes sacred, the Speech and Debate Clause.","start":4033.156,"stop":4066.918,"duration":33.76},{"text":"I thank you.","start":4066.918,"stop":4069.83,"duration":2.91}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Miss Rosenberg.","start":4069.83,"stop":4072.56,"duration":2.73}]},{"speakerName":"Beatrice Rosenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"May I please the Court.","start":4072.56,"stop":4074.296,"duration":1.74},{"text":"I am rather surprised to find that the Professor is making a distinction between speech and vote for the purposes of the Speech and Debate Clause because the case of Coffin against Coffin which this Court decided in (Inaudible) as the authoritative decision on the Speech and Debate Clause makes it very clear in this Court's decision in the Kilbourn against Thompson, decision in (Inaudible) made clear that the State's Speech and Debate Clause covers all official action taken in the capacity as represented to speech, vote, committee report, anything of that character.","start":4074.296,"stop":4126.282,"duration":51.99},{"text":"Now, to the English history, what's Strode's was a case of someone who in colonies introduced the bill regulating tanneries.","start":4126.282,"stop":4138.127,"duration":11.85},{"text":"I think it turns now that one of the books that he was a tenant but nothing has ever turned on that.","start":4138.127,"stop":4143.307,"duration":5.18},{"text":"What happened is that when he got back to his local district, where the act that he was in favor of would have affected the local industry.","start":4143.307,"stop":4154.337,"duration":11.03},{"text":"The local Government, which was called the (Inaudible) tried to prosecute him for introducing these bills in Congress.","start":4154.337,"stop":4164.274,"duration":9.94},{"text":"And the problem, I'm sorry -- and at that point, Parliament passed this resolution saying that no -- for what he did in Parliament, he could not be prosecuted, in this case by a local, equivalent to our county Government.","start":4164.274,"stop":4183.551,"duration":19.28},{"text":"Now, that became -- Strode case did become a kind of slogan case thereafter in the long fight between parliament and the crown, which I wouldn't have to -- have time to go and to now, but I've point out two things about the English history.","start":4183.551,"stop":4204.238,"duration":20.69},{"text":"One is that the Speech and Debate, the right of Parliament to talk about anything -- which was divided during Elizabeth's time.","start":4204.238,"stop":4212.268,"duration":8.03},{"text":"They question whether the Parliament could talk about the succession for the religious questions which are coming up.","start":4212.268,"stop":4220.141,"duration":7.87},{"text":"That question was settled by 1689 in the English Bill of Right.","start":4220.141,"stop":4226.122,"duration":5.98},{"text":"The period of the 18th century in England was a period when Parliament was trying to get for itself, not simply the right to talk about anything, but the right completely to regulate its own members and anybody that dealt with its own members.","start":4226.122,"stop":4242.094,"duration":15.97},{"text":"And that period was a period, as a matter of fact, when the crown was trying to bribe Congressmen so they are not English prosecutions for bribery, but that alleged Parliament, the right of Parliament to govern itself and even govern people that dealt with it.","start":4242.094,"stop":4260.334,"duration":18.24},{"text":"Exclusively, this Court has held was not taken over into American law and if it's --as the Court pointed it out in the Watkins case, they founders of our Constitution were very worried about legislative excess.","start":4260.334,"stop":4278.919,"duration":18.59},{"text":"They were -- that was one of the things they tried to guard against and so, the Lex Parliamentary has never been part of the American law.","start":4278.919,"stop":4288.026,"duration":9.11},{"text":"The absence of English cases therefore is not controlling, but it is interesting that the only time the questions of bribery statutes have come up for decisions.","start":4288.026,"stop":4299.521,"duration":11.49},{"text":"There have been state bribery prosecutions but nobody raised any problems in the Speech and Debate Clause.","start":4299.521,"stop":4305.56,"duration":6.04},{"text":"The only time that the question of the Speech and Debate Clause in relation to prosecutions for bribery of Congressman has been brought up are in three Colonial cases which are on page 34 of our main brief and in those, there was only one dissenting vote and the dissent was on the ground of Lex Parliamentaria.","start":4305.56,"stop":4329.355,"duration":23.79},{"text":"The other three cases all have that -- it was possible -- they -- some of them said that it was a crime at Common Law to take a bribe and all of them incidentally, in the English has been showing its relations to the Lex Parliamentary considered that if you couldn't prosecute a Congressman for taking a bribe, you couldn't prosecute the person that gave him the bribe.","start":4329.355,"stop":4357.979,"duration":28.62},{"text":"That is their version, in other words, they approached the question pretty much.","start":4357.979,"stop":4363.19,"duration":5.21},{"text":"Did come within the Lex Parliamentary or it didn't.","start":4363.19,"stop":4367.177,"duration":3.99},{"text":"And, as I say, this Court has made it clear from the time of the Anderson against Dunn, to the time of Watkins that Lex Parliamentaria is not a part of American law, which we took over from Great Britain.","start":4367.177,"stop":4381.538,"duration":14.36},{"text":"So that from the purposes of the Speech and Debate Clause, I do not see that there is any possibility of drawing a distinction between the speech and above.","start":4381.538,"stop":4393.581,"duration":12.04},{"text":"And, as far as the actual coverage of 0205 is concerned, in 1862, when it was passed on the floor of the House, the expressions were said that it was comprehensive as man could make it.","start":4393.581,"stop":4411.679,"duration":18.1},{"text":"As for the argument that has been made here that -- well, it wouldn't have come within 1205 because at that moment, there was no legislation pending.","start":4411.679,"stop":4422.518,"duration":10.84},{"text":"That old Massachusetts Coffin case that the -- even though it was physically said in the floor of the House, if it wasn't in relation to legislative matters, it wasn't with the speech within the Speech and Debate Clause, we have never contended that.","start":4422.518,"stop":4436.973,"duration":14.45},{"text":"We admit that this is when the -- that is the speech itself is within the Speech and Debate Clause.","start":4436.973,"stop":4442.469,"duration":5.5},{"text":"It is our position that when you have a prosecution for taking money to give a speech, the act which is being questioned is the taking of the money.","start":4442.469,"stop":4458.832,"duration":16.36},{"text":"Now, in that kind of a prosecution, we admit it will -- it was brought out here and it was shown that the speech was given.","start":4458.832,"stop":4468.911,"duration":10.08},{"text":"This was also alleged in the indictment but the prosecution rested on the proof that the speech was prepared with a purpose in line, that it was used for that purpose, that money did go to the Congressman.","start":4468.911,"stop":4490.868,"duration":21.96},{"text":"And, let me say one thing about that, the theory -- the reason this prosecution was brought under 371 and not to violate specific statute, was that it was the theory and we think it's established by the evidence that this Congressman was, -- I just want to say, put on pay roll to do the thing that were to be done.","start":4490.868,"stop":4517.089,"duration":26.22},{"text":"The speech was part of that.","start":4517.089,"stop":4518.785,"duration":1.7},{"text":"It was not all of it.","start":4518.785,"stop":4520.101,"duration":1.32},{"text":"The rest of it and the most important part goes up later with the representations for the Department of Justice.","start":4520.101,"stop":4530.129,"duration":10.03},{"text":"But, this does not mean that the Government takes the position that $500.00 was all that was given for the speech.","start":4530.129,"stop":4540.26,"duration":10.13}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Nov  11, 1965; Nov  15, 1965","petitioner":"United States","respondent":"Johnson","docket":"25","citation":"383 US 169 (1966)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/383/169","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Feb 24, 1966"}